<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>They Don't Call It Brainland </title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#001F76" vlink="#001F76"
alink="#001F76">

<blockquote>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <h2>from the pages of<img src="oldsmzma.gif" alt="../"
        align="top" hspace="4" width="108" height="37"> </h2>
    </blockquote>
    <hr>
    <h1 align="center">They Don't Call It Brainland </h1>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em>Bob Harris </em></font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em></em></font>&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p>The Big Story here in Cleveland, page one of the Plain
        Dealer, repeated with furrowed brows on all the newscasts:
        The Browns (a football team, not a slang term for the
        Wise Use movement) are threatening to blow town for St.
        Louis or Baltimore if the taxpayers don't fork up some gigabucks
        to put shag rug on the goal posts. Here we go again. This
        is after the good Clevo working folk delivered over $300
        million in small unmarked bills to the real estate billionaire Jacobs
        Brothers to keep our beloved baseball Indians from losing
        their hundred games a year in St. Petersburg. </p>
        <p>The result? A state-of-the-art baseball/basketball
        Athletic Complex (which describes our psychological affliction
        nicely): big shiny scoreboards; big shiny racist Chief
        Wahoo logos ten feet high; big shiny multi-tiered
        restaurants so the big shiny ad execs eating $100 dinners can look
        down at the proles in their twice-as-expensive-as-last-year
        seats drinking $3 beers; even a big shiny underground
        passageway to the downtown train terminal so suburbanites won't
        soil themselves by actual contact with the city folk above. </p>
        <p>They call it &quot;Gateway.&quot; </p>
        <p>Um<193>Gateway to what, exactly? This is Cleveland, people.
        Cleveland hasn't been a gateway to anything since the
        Louisiana Purchase. </p>
        <p>Well, yeah, there's a bit of the Clevo skyline visible
        past the outfield. A couple of smallish office buildings.
        Whoopee. Gateway to Amway. </p>
        <p>But there's a reason the stadium's pointed in that
        direction. It's also walking distance from closed-down factories
        on the third base side and some of the poorest
        neighborhoods in the midwest behind the first base line. </p>
        <p>In truth, the stadium is a Gateway, as from one world
        to another--them what gots on the inside, them what don'ts
        on the out. It's the Gateway to the Supercapitalist
        future, as the shrinking middle class, thoroughly propagandized
        on the virtue of unfettered private gain, gladly amuses itself
        by financing the richest segments of society while
        literally, physically turning their backs on all who
        represent the system's failures. </p>
        <p>Tradition. That's what baseball's all about. </p>
        <p>Even the names of the individual facilities fairly
        drip with greed. The baseball park has been dubbed Jacobs
        Field, modestly enough, but only because they couldn't
        find a corporation willing to drop $20 million to buy the
        name as ad space; if the cash was right, Clevelanders might
        be watching ballgames at K-Mart Park, the Spam Palace, or
        the Clapper Dome. (This last would really be cool during
        night games.) Likewise, the Cavaliers' new basketball facility
        is named for their owners, the Gund brothers. The result is,
        um, unfortunate: Gund Arena. </p>
        <p>Say it a few times rapidly and you'll see the problem.
        Go on, I'll wait. See? Isn't that great? </p>
        <p>The inevitable radio ads are outstanding. &quot;Gund
        Arena. Be where the action is.&quot; &quot;Gund Arena's
        great for the whole family.&quot; And the apparently-related,
        &quot;Cavs Fever-Catch it.&quot; The Family Values crowd must
        not monitor sports radio. At the first exhibition, the PA
        announcer welcomed the crowd to &quot;your new Gund Arena.&quot;
        I wouldn't know whether to applaud or take an antibiotic. </p>
        <p>The name is only temporary until the team is sold to
        the Painful Rectal Inflammation family of Akron. </p>
        <p>So, anyway, with a gift from the citizens in excess of
        $400 million (including cost overruns and miscellaneous
        perks), how did the bazillionaires of baseball respond?
        By fielding the best Cleveland baseball team since you
        could buy a Cuban cigar--in fact, the only one not to suck
        that I'm personally old enough to have witnessed. By
        raking in record amounts of cash from sellout crowds
        night after night. By receiving the most joyful
        enthusiasm this grim village has generated in memory,
        loyal adoration almost intense enough to cause one to
        look away from the massive boondoggle. And then, by
        stopping. </p>
        <p>By not even having the decency to play out their first
        full season. Because they weren't making enough money.
        The bastards. </p>
        <p>So will we learn anything from all this? Not hardly. </p>
        <p>As to the park itself, I can't imagine a greater
        symbol of the extent to which politics has become simply
        a profit machine greased by childish thinking. </p>
        <p>Right at the junction of Interstates 90 and 70--come
        and see--stands a nicely-shaped piece of metal that cost
        roughly a half a billion bucks. From our pockets. Empty,
        because the guys who own it are pissed that they're not
        richer. </p>
        <p>And the Chamber of Commerce points to it with pride.
        Duh. </p>
        <p>We've got Gateway, everybody, and the Rock and Roll
        Hall of Fame (don't get me started on that now), and to
        watch the hair and teeth on the evening news here you'd
        swear they think all this just might make the city's
        intolerable segregation, poverty, and infant mortality
        rate somehow magically disappear. </p>
        <p>Half a billion bucks. Hell, we could have had a
        Stealth fighter for that kind of money. (And wouldn't
        that be cool in the playoffs? We'd kick Chicago's ass.)
        And now, no shock, Browns owner Art Modell, who is constantly
        portrayed in this town as being among the least greedy of NFL owners--which
        is a bit like calling Savonarola one of the nicest members of
        the Inquisition--says that if we don't give him and the Browns
        a similar blowjob, he just might have to find a town that
        will. </p>
        <p>What happens? Do the citizens of Cleveland go and find
        this guy, line up single file, and begin just slapping
        him over and over and over? You want what? (Slap.) $200
        million? (Slap.) Or else<193>you'll just leave? (Slap. Slap.
        Slap.) Oh, nooooo. (Sarcastic laughter, enthusiastic slapping.
        Line extends to Ashtabula.) </p>
        <p>No. Instead, the mayor, Mike White, mounts a soapbox
        on his knees, spouting the standard delusional economic
        theories about how paying some rich guy hundreds of
        millions of dollars to host eight football games a year
        will somehow revitalize the economic lives of the folks on East 105th
        Street. </p>
        <p>Worse, the city's bigshots aren't stopping with the
        Browns. No, there's enough money to be taken this way they're
        coming positively unhinged. Heck, let's build new hotels,
        and a new Convention Center, and even a Casino on Lake
        Erie. Sure, bigshots from Singapore are just dying to visit
        Ohio in February to play blackjack until dawn. </p>
        <p>That's what I call a responsible economic plan. And
        people are falling for it. </p>
        <p>Grow up, Cleveland. Let the Browns go. Turn the old
        stadium into the Sacred Shrine to the Severed Head of
        Bernie Kosar. Spend your money on the neighborhoods--pass
        some school levies, people--and your Sundays with your
        families (you know, those people in the house who never
        seem to leave). </p>
        <p>Set an example for the rest of America. In a real
        Major League City, the hopes of the citizens depend not on
        who's playing today, but who's working tomorrow. </p>
        <p><em>Bob Harris is a comic, and does a progressive TV
        talk show in Cleveland.</em> </p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
