<head>
<title>Albert Lecture from LOLU course on Econ Vision</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body stylesrc="../archive/index.htm">

<p><a><img src="../gifs/smlolu.gif" alt="LOLU | " align="middle"
hspace="4" width="144" height="71"> </a><a href="../index.htm"><img
src="../gifs/smznet.gif" alt="ZNet | " align="middle" border="0"
hspace="4" width="73" height="37"> </a><a href="../help.htm"><img
src="../gifs/help.gif" alt="HELP | " align="middle" border="0"
hspace="4" width="56" height="54"></a> <a
href="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><img src="../gifs/feedback.gif"
alt="Feedback" align="middle" border="0" hspace="4" width="90"
height="46"> </a></p>

<hr>

<h1>Economic Vision: Lecture 1</h1>

<address>
    Introduction: What is an economy and what aims might we have
    for an economy
</address>

<address>
    Faculty: Michael Albert
</address>

<hr>

<hr>

<h2>A. Getting Started</h2>

<p>The idea of this course is a bit unusual. We are not only
trying to develop our understanding of particular existing
economic visions, which would be fine all by itself. We also want
to develop an ability to think about and create economic vision,
more or less from scratch, on our own.</p>

<p>Here is the tentative outline of lecture topics. They may
change somewhat in light of interests, the pace the course
actually goes at, etc. (Notice, the outline doesn't give away too
much of the plot...)</p>

<ul>
    <li>Introduction: What is an economy and what aims might we
        have for an economy </li>
    <li>Existing Visionary Options (market, centrally planned,
        social democratic, anarchist...)</li>
    <li>Production 1: Conceptualizing general aims for workplaces
        and work</li>
    <li>Consumption 1: Conceptualizing general aims for
        consumption</li>
    <li>Allocation 1: Conceptualizing general aims for allocation</li>
    <li>Production 2: Defining workplace decision making
        structure, job roles and work</li>
    <li>Consumption 2: Conceiving desirable remuneration and
        consumption decision making</li>
    <li>Allocation 2: Defining criteria of decision making,
        motivations, information issues, choice issues,/
        allocation institutions and roles</li>
    <li>Economic Aims in context of society as a whole</li>
    <li>Thinking about Transition/Program/Strategy</li>
</ul>

<h2>B. What is this course's purpose?</h2>

<p>As some of you likely know, I thought up (with Robin Hahnel)
the vision called Participatory Economics. Part of the aim of the
course is to understand it, and also the visions called
&quot;market socialism,&quot; and centrally planned
socialism.&quot; But what I am also hoping is that we will
develop an ability to judge these systems and even to think up
adaptations or entirely different models. </p>

<p>Therefore the aim of the course is to learn how to conceive of
an economic vision, to learn about a few (and one in particular),
and to develop an ability to judge economies and economic
visions. </p>

<h2>C. The Mechanics of the Course</h2>

<p>To even begin to accomplish these ends as a first, preliminary
step, we have to know (a) what is an economy, (b) what aims do we
want an economy (our economic vision) to accomplish.</p>

<p>Knowing (a) what an economy is tells us what we have to
describe and explain in order to have described and explained an
economic vision. Knowing (b) what aims we have for economic life
and activity tells us what characteristics and qualities we have
to build into the economy we favor.</p>

<p>Before getting to these introductory issues, however--and they
are the main focus of this first lecture and do set a foundation
for much that follows--let's do a little introducing--and
scene-setting.</p>

<p>Each week I will post a lecture. I am going to try to be
conversational and clear, but not simplistic. Each lecture will
take us part way to where I want the class to be by the time of
the next lecture, but not all the way. Getting the rest of the
way is going to require some work on everyone's part during the
subsequent week. After all, you can't learn new ways of thinking
and evaluating without some practice. To facilitate
participation, in each lecture I will ask a bunch of questions.
Settling on answers will get us where we need to be for the
subsequent lecture. </p>

<p>During the week following each lecture I hope many of you will
react to what I have offered, ask questions about whatever you
find confusing, suggest improvements to anything you think is
inadequate, raise related issues that interest you, and also, as
a priority, try to provide answers to the questions I raise
preparatory to delivering the next lecture. (The best way to do
that, by the way, is to compose your answer after reading the
lecture, but independently of other people's answers. The more
independent answers we get to questions, up to a point, the
better.) In any event, answers to the questions I ask are going
to be needed in order to proceed with the next lecture.</p>

<p>Sometimes questions I raise will have many viable answers.
Other times, there may be one right answer. During each week I
will try to relate to everyone's comments and questions and I
will certainly relate to answers to the questions I offer in the
lectures, prodding until we get what we need to continue the next
week.</p>

<p>You can send me EMail if you would like to communicate in
private. And I may send a message or two privately as well. The
fact is, I have no more experience teaching a class this way than
any (most?) of you have taking one this way. We are going to
learn the limits and assets of this approach together. The main
thing, I think, is when you have a question ask it, when you
disagree about something put your different view forward, and
let's all remember this is a learning experience, not a shoot-out
at the OK Corral. There actually aren't going to be all that many
of us--probably about twenty or so, so it ought to be quite
manageable.</p>

<p>As one &quot;assignment&quot; for this first week, finally,
could each student write a brief personal message, briefly
describing yourself and your prior knowledge or lack of knowledge
in the field, indicating your reasons for taking this course. A
little background about each student will be good, I think, to
help us interact and also to help me prepare lectures.</p>

<h2>(I) What is an Economy?</h2>

<p>How the hell do we answer a question like this? I suppose we
could go look it up somewhere, but the idea in this course is to
create our own answers, not to go find and repeat someone elses.</p>

<p>So, how about if we take it a step at a time. What happens in
an economy? </p>

<p>Well, people consume and produce things. So let's start with
that: an economy is the set of institutions that facilitate and
organize people producing and consuming things. </p>

<p>What then is production, what is consumption, what is an
institution, and what does &quot;facilitate and organize&quot;
mean?</p>

<h3>Production:</h3>

<p>Well, regarding production, when it happens something new
generally emerges. And, it doesn't emerge from nothing, but from
stuff that is combined together in the act of production. So we
have inputs to production and outputs from it. The inputs are
combined, the outputs are the result. The action undertaked in
the middle, is called work. The places where this happens we will
call workplaces. </p>

<p>Okay, so what are the inputs and what are the outputs of
typical production processes?</p>

<p>This is the first question that we need to answer to be ready
for lecture two. (I'll get you started. Answer for an auto plant.
One thing that goes in is rubber. One that comes out is a Honda.
But there is much more...) But let's do it &quot;in class&quot;
during the week. For now, let's just go on as if we already had
the answer. You might want to think about it, before
continuing...and I hope many of you will answer it, in your own
way, in messages, before you read other people's posts, as part
of your first reaction this coming week.</p>

<p>Next, knowing what the inputs and outputs of production are,
how do we describe workplaces? They are institutions you might
say. Fine. But what is that? What is the critical attribute that
defines institutions, and that distinguishes one from another? </p>

<p>Is it the floorplan? Is it the size of the building, or even
the existence of a building? Is it the speed things happen at?
The quality of the results? These characteristics are important,
but not at the heart of the matter, I think we can agree. Then
what?</p>

<p>Well, we know that there is something similar that is
profoundly important, about, say, GM, Microsoft, and the local
cannery. This is what we want to get a grip on. And it isn't
their size, their products, their buildings, their locales. They
have almost nothing in common on these axes. What they share is
instead something about the relations that exist, day in and day
out, among the actors who get together in these institutions.
Something about their motivations, interests, behaviours, and
choices. This is what we really mean, it seems to me, when we
refer to an institution.</p>

<p>So how about if we say that an institution is a collection of
social roles (plus some infrastructure and perhaps equipment, and
the people who fill the roles). By social roles we mean things
like union steward, mother, judge, manager, CEO, owner, worker.
Then, the critical things that is similar about the businesses
mentioned above, all of which are capitalist, is that they all
embody the same basic defining role structures. In different
economies it follows that we will have qualitatively different
types of economic institutions due to their having qualitatively
different role structures.</p>

<p>So, in any economy, we have workplaces which have role
structures and in which production takes place. There are inputs
and outputs. If we are going to define an economic vision, part
of the job will be defining these production institutions, and
particularly their role structures.</p>

<p>What are the primary roles within capitalist workplaces? </p>

<p>Is a public school a workplace, a GM factory, a family? Why or
why not?</p>

<h3>Consumption:</h3>

<p>Now we have something to go with. One important part of the
art of doing theoretical work, of understanding some domain or
envisioning one, is to develop concepts and then build on them,
only adding new ones when they are really needed. We have defined
one type of economic activity, production. We have said it has
inputs and outputs (which we will describe this week) and we have
said that it is carried out in production institutions, which we
call workplaces, and that these have role structures (that we
will also address during the week in our messages) that are what
give them their defining features.</p>

<p>So what about consumption? Well, we immediately know that it
is another economic activity. It too has inputs and outputs. It
too is carried out in context of institutions, and we can call
them consumption institutions. And they too have role structures.</p>

<p>And now we have some more questions we need to deal with
during this coming week:</p>

<p>What are the inputs and outputs of consumption activity? </p>

<p>What distinguishes consumption activity from production
activity? </p>

<p>What are some consumption activity roles?</p>

<p>Is a factory, a school, a family a consumption institution?
Why or why not? </p>

<h3>Allocation:</h3>

<p>Now we return to the sticky question of facilitating and
organizing the economic activities production and consumption.
What does this entail?</p>

<p>Well, we know that there are a whole lot of people consuming
and producing, and we know that there are a whole lot of places
where all this activity goes on. Allocation is the name we give
for the institutions by which and through which it is determined
what the inputs and outputs of the economy's activities will be
and where they will wind up.</p>

<p>In each production institution, what is produced, how much,
with what steps, by whom? For each person and group of people,
what is consumed, how much, and how is it gotten? How does what
is produced come to match what is sought for consumption and vice
versa. How do outputs match up with inputs?</p>

<p>The market is an allocation institution. And so is a central
planning apparatus. And we might dream up some others as well,
including say, decentralizing the economy into little separate
self-sufficient units so that allocation is carried on entirely
as a face-to-face exchange.</p>

<p>Once we think of markets as an institution we know that we
need to describe the associated role structure. Likewise if we
think of central planning this way, again, we have to describe
the roles that are associated with central planning. For markets
we have buyers and sellers. There may be other refinements in a
particular market economy, but we could go a long way toward
figuring out the defining features of markets if we revealed the
motivations and behaviors of these buyers and sellers and how
their behaviors combine to influence allocation. For central
planning we have order givers (planners) and order takers
(workers)...</p>

<p>And, likewise, for any economic vision we will need to do the
same thing, describe the allocation institution in terms of the
roles that it defines for economic actors and the ensuing
dynamics and processes and their implications for who does what,
who gets what, etc.</p>

<p>What is investment and what does it have to do with
allocation?</p>

<p>In a market economy, what determines how much of the product
each actor gets?</p>

<p>And what determines, in a market economy, how much work each
actor does? </p>

<p>So to define an economy we need to define production,
consumption, and allocation institutions that work successfully
together. That will be our goal. But, of course, not just any
such institutions. We want ones that have qualities we like.</p>

<h2>(II) Evaluating an Economy, and our Aims</h2>

<p>Economies affect people. This is pretty obvious, but important
to understand in a bit more detail. They influence what we do (by
providing roles we have to fill) and what we get from the
productive output (by allocations outcomes). These two facts in
turn have much to do with our possible life stories. Are we doing
interesting or boring things at work? Do we have power over our
circumstances or are we bossed around by others? Do we starve,
get by, or enjoy luxury. What happens to our personalities and
potentials in the work we do and consuming we opt for? And so on.</p>

<p>Evaluating an economy means asking how do its institutions
affect people? What are the built-in implications for people's
lives of the economy's production, consumption, and allocation
institutions/roles when they are operating as they are meant to?
If the economy propels anti-social attitudes or distorts and
underutilizes human capabilities, or if it rewards people
unjustly, these would be issues to take up in evaluating it. To
make a judgment we must have some values, some norms for what is
good and what is bad in economic life. </p>

<p>And the issue isn't so much some specific economic event,
perhaps a mistake, say, or the act of a psychopath, but the
built-in dynamics of the economy and their inevitable
implications for people's lives. So what would we like an economy
to achieve in the way of broad general aims?</p>

<p>There are many possible answers.</p>

<p>We might want an economy to simply maximize output for our
society. The economy that can yield the biggest pile of produced
stuff is the one we want, regardless of other effects. We might
want an economy which ensures that some set of people get the
most possible stuff, regardless of the overall amount produced or
what anyone else gets. We might want an economy which yields
identical outcomes for everyone in the society, regardless of
output, or with the largest output consistent with that degree of
equality. And so on.</p>

<p>I am going to propose some broad goals: equity, solidarity,
diversity, participatory self management, plus efficiency, and,
by implication, classlessness.</p>

<p>We could argue about these, I suppose, forever. And maybe we
should have some of that in our interactions. My reasons for
choosing these as the economic aims I want to see embodied in an
economy probably stem from all manner of things--you cannot
arrive at values purely by reason. But, I think among leftists
they should be pretty uncontroversial, save insofar as we might
wonder if a system can address them all simultaneously.</p>

<p>Thus, equity says we should have fair or just outcomes. No one
should get more of a good thing, or of a bad thing, than he or
she deserves. We will talk more about what determines how much
one deserves later&lt;193&gt;</p>

<p>Solidarity means the economy should foster empathy among
people, mutual respect and caring, rather than an attitude that
you are my enemy or, in any event, I don't care about your well
being.</p>

<p>Diversity merely testifies to a belief that homogeneity is
boring and we all benefit from diverse outcomes. Partly this is
because it is a good hedge against errors. Partly it is because
life is short and we can enjoy other people's different
involvements vicariously, etc.</p>

<p>Finally, participatory self management means that each person
should have a fair share of say over his or her own life. We
should be able to affect the decisions that in turn affect us,
and we should be able to do it in proportion as we are in turn
affected.</p>

<p>The claim is simple, in an economy, other things equal, if we
have more of these attributes, it is better. If we have less it
is worse.</p>

<p>At the same time, the economic function should be carried out
without waste (efficiency).</p>

<p>Classlessness is derivative because if you have classes, as
compared to not having them, you are worse on all these values.
class division reduces equity, curtails solidarity, reduces
diversity, and limits self management.</p>

<p>So, we can take our goals as the four noted, or as
classlessness, plus within the bounds of meeting those values,
economic efficiency.</p>

<p>For discussion purposes, if anyone wishes to argue that some
desirable value we would like to see implemented is left out if
we take these as our guides, please do. Or, for that matter, if
anyone wants to question any of this, likewise, please do. </p>

<p>My own personal justification for them is that they seem to me
to be consistent with and necessary for a maximum of personal
fulfillment and development for each individual and for the whole
population as a collective, consistent with the just norm that
everyone should have as good a shot at fulfillment and
development as anyone else.</p>

<p>These are going to be the values that guide my choices during
the class, but if anyone wants us to take into account others as
well, or instead, please suggest them.</p>

<h2>(III) A summary of critical questions for message posting
during Week One of EconVision:</h2>

<p>What are the inputs, and what are the outputs of production
processes?</p>

<p>What are the primary roles within capitalist workplaces? </p>

<p>Is a public school a workplace, a GM factory, a family? Why or
why not?</p>

<p>What are the inputs and outputs of consumption activity? </p>

<p>What distinguishes consumption activity from production
activity? </p>

<p>What are some consumption activity roles?</p>

<p>Is a factory, a school, a family a consumption institution?
Why or why not? </p>

<p>What is investment and what does it have to do with
allocation?</p>

<p>In a market economy, what determines how much of the product
each actor gets?</p>

<p>And what determines, in a market economy, how much work each
actor does? </p>

<p>P.S. : Each week, if any of you have any criticisms or other
comments you would like to convey privately, feel free to use
E-Mail. Advice on future lectures is always welcome, of course.
But questions about content, should, if possible, be asked in
class. </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
