<H1>
Course Outline--Consumerism in the U.S. Course</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Faculty: Juliet Schor</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<P>Greetings to all participants in the course on Consumerism in the United
States today. Welcome. I thought I would begin with a brief description of what
this course will be about, and then I have a few logistical details.</P>
<P>Some personal history: In 1992 I published a book called The Overworked
American: The Unexpected Decline of Leisure (New York: Basic Books). The premise
of that book was that working hours have been rising in the United States since
the late 1960s, and that many Americans are now &quot;overworked&quot; and
stressed out. Instead of the leisure society which was predicted as a result of
automation and mechanization, we have become ever more enslaved to our jobs. The
attendant social consequences are predictable: families without enough time to
be together, children whose parents aren't around enough, growing unemployment
as work hours are concentrated among fewer and fewer employees, a decline of
sleep, a rise in stress, less time for volunteering and civic participation,
excessive business in daily life, erosion of community, etc. </P>
<P>In order to understand how this has happened, I developed the idea of the &quot;work
and spend&quot; cycle, and argued that our nation had become enmeshed in this
dynamic. In this course, we will begin with that idea, focussing mainly on the
spending side of it (after an initial section on work and worktimes). Why are we
such a &quot;spendaholic&quot; nation? What dynamics are at work? What is the
role of advertising in our consumerism? Television and mass media? What is the
impact of social pressure,i.e., keeping up with the Joneses&quot;?
Status-seeking? Are Americans obsessed with novelty? Where is our consumerism &quot;coming
from&quot;?</P>
<P>We will also look at the consequences of consumerist society--
environmental, cultural, economic, human. We will discuss alternatives to
consumerism, such as simple living, and the voluntary simplicity movement
sspringing up around the country. We will consider the economic and political
obstacles to a less consumerist society. Is it even possible in capitalism? 
</P>
<P>I am currently at work on a new book on consumerism (still in the research
phase). I will share my new research with you and will be interested to get your
feedback and reactions. </P>
<P>The format and procedures of the course will be this: Every weekend I will
write a lecture, which will be posted by Sunday evening at 9 pm EST. The first
lecture will come this Sunday. I will also post readings which relate to the
lecture, including two categories of readings: those which are strongly
recommended and very close to the topic, and those which are slightly less
close, but allow you to pursue the issues further or deeper. These correspond to
the usual classroom distinction between &quot;required&quot; and &quot;recommended&quot;
readings. Of course, in this session, no reading is required. You can just read
my lectures and follow the class discussion. However, you will get more out of
the course if you also do reading. Throughout the week, you will be able to
raise questions, make comments, etc. And I will respond to your
comments/messages when I post the next week's lecture. All substantive issues
should be referred to me. All technical questions about communicating online
should go to the ZBBS system operator.</P>
<P>Between now and Sunday, when I return, it would be nice if those of you who
are planning to take the course could &quot;introduce&quot; yourselves, with a
short discussion of who you are and your interest in the topic of consumerism.
</P>
<P>I look forward to &quot;meeting&quot; all of you. Juliet Schor </P>
</BODY></HTML>
