<H1>
Course Outline--Introduction to Political Economy</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Instructor: Robin Hahnel, Professor, Department of Economics
The American University, Washington DC 20016 Phone: 202-885-2712; Fax
202-885-3790</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<P>Week 1: What are economies? How is the economic sphere of social life
related to other spheres of social life? How should we evaluate the performance
of economies?</P>
<P>Readings (readings are all optional, the course can be followed solely
paying attention to on line lectures):</P>
<P>Albert, Cagan, Chomsky, Hahnel, King, Sargent, Sklar,   Liberating Theory
(Boston: South End Press, 1986),   Chapters 1-6; pp. 5-93.</P>
<P>Hahnel and Albert, Quiet Revolution in Welfare Economics,   (Princeton:
Princeton University Press, 1990), [QR]   Chapters 5 and 6*.</P>
<P>Albert and Hahnel, The Political Economy of Participatory   Economics
(Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1991),   [PEPE] pp. 7-11.</P>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P>Weeks 2,3,4: Different ways of deciding What to produce? How to produce it?
How to use it? Classes, Oppression, and Exploitation.</P>
<P>Readings:</P>
<P>&quot;The Professional Managerial Class&quot; by Barbara and John  
Ehrenreich, &quot;Intellectuals and the Class Structure of   Capitalist Society&quot;
by Erik Olin Wright, and &quot;A Ticket to   Ride: More Locations on the Class
Map&quot; by Albert and   Hahnel all in Pat Walker, ed., Between Labor and
Capital   (Boston: South End Press, 1979),</P>
<P>John Roemer, Free to Lose (Cambridge: Harvard University   Press, 1988),
Chapters 2,5,6* and 7*.</P>
<HR>
<P>Weeks 5,6: Markets: What they Do and How to Evaluate Them. Invisible Hand or
Invisible Foot? Equity and Social Effects.</P>
<P>Readings:</P>
<P>Bradley Schiller, The Economy Today, 6th ed. (NY: McGraw   Hill, 1994),
[Schiller] Chapter 3.</P>
<P>Robert Heilbroner, The Worldly Philosophers, 6th ed. (NY:   Simon and
Schuster), Chapter III.</P>
<P>[QR] pp. 61-64; 226-240.</P>
<P>Samuel Bowles, &quot;What Markets Can and Cannot Do,&quot; in   Challenge
Magazine, July-August 1991.</P>
<P>Albert and Hahnel, &quot;Why Participatory Planning,&quot; in Z   Papers,
April-June 1994, pp. 25-32.</P>
<HR>
<P>Weeks 7,8,9: The Collapse of Communism and the debate between Capitalism,
Market &quot;Socialism,&quot; and Participatory Economics.</P>
<P>Readings:</P>
<P>David Kotz, &quot;The Collapse of State Socialism in the USSR:   Lessons for
a Future Socialism.&quot;</P>
<P>Hahnel and Albert, &quot;Revolutions in the East,&quot; in Z   Magazine,
April 1990.</P>
<P>Milton Friedman, Capitalism and Freedom, (Chicago:   University of Chicago
Press, 1982), Introduction and   Chapters I,II, and X.</P>
<P>[PEPE] Chapters 1,2,3,4,5*</P>
<P>Albert and Hahnel, &quot;Why Participatory Planning,&quot; in Z   Papers,
July-August 1994, pp. 32-47.</P>
<P>Articles by Thomas Weisskopf, David Schweickart, Albert   and Hahnel, and
Pat Devine in the special issue on the   &quot;Future of Socialism&quot; of the
Review of Radical Political   Economics, Fall-Winter 1992, Vol. 24 Nos. 3&amp;4.
(URPE C/O   Department of Economics, University of California at   Riverside,
Riverside CA 92521)</P>
<P>&quot;Economic Roundtable on Looking Forward&quot; in Z Magazine,  
July-August 1991.</P>
<P>John Roemer, &quot;A Future for Socialism&quot; in the Newsletter   of the
Committee on the Political Economy of the Good   Society, Winter 1993.</P>
<P>Robin Hahnel, &quot;Book Review of A Future for Socialism,&quot; in   Z
Magazine, October 1994.</P>
<HR>
<P>Weeks 10,11,12: The Macroeconomics of Capitalism: Causes of unemployment and
inflation; The logic of fiscal and monetary policy; Politics of the budget;
Schools of thought. Comparisons between US, Japanese, French, British, and
Swedish Capitalisms.</P>
<P>Readings:</P>
<P>[Schiller] Chapters 5,6,8,9,10; 11,12,13,14,15</P>
<HR>
<P>Weeks 13,14: International Economics: What Causes Trade? How to Interpret
Balance of Payments. Mutual Benefit or Imperialism?</P>
<P>Readings:</P>
<P>Peter Lindert, International Economics, 9th ed., (Boston:   Richard Irwin,
1991), Chapters 2,3,4*</P>
<P>[Schiller] Chapters 35 and 17</P>
<P>Robin Hahnel, &quot;Cooperacion International, Si! NAFTA, No!&quot;   in Z
Magazine, April 1993.</P>
<HR>
<P>Week 15: Markets and Environmental Destruction: The Political Economy of
Environmental Regulation.</P>
<P>Readings:</P>
<P>[Schiller] Chapter 28   Eban Goodstein, Economics and the Environment, (NJ: 
 Prentice Hall, 1995) Chapters 1,2, and 3.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
