<HR>
<H1>
Political Economy: Lecture 3</H1>
<H2>Different Economic Visions</H2>
<ADDRESS>Faculty: Robin Hahnel</ADDRESS>
<HR>
<P>The simplest way to organize economic activities is for every person to
produce everything she wants to consume and consume everything she produces.
That is, for every person to be totally self-sufficient. This is the &quot;autarkic&quot;
solution to the economic problem and has never been used because (1) human
beings are a social species and have never been inclined to &quot;go it alone&quot;
except under extreme and temporary conditions of geographical isolation, and (2)
this solution is very inefficient compared to solutions where people specialize
in some production task(s) and &quot;trade&quot; with others who specialize in
other tasks, since greater &quot;division of labor&quot; can permit greater
overall productivity.</P>
<P>Every other solution to the economic problem involves organizing and
coordinating the interdependent activities of people. This is always done via
major economic institutions that combine into some particular kind of &quot;economic
system&quot; that governs production, consumption, and allocation.</P>
<P>Every economic system must decide:</P>
<P>(1) What to produce (and what not to produce.)</P>
<P>(2) How much of each kind of good or service   to produce.</P>
<P>(3) How to produced each good or service,   since there is usually more than
one way to   produce things.</P>
<P>(4) Who will consume what goods and services.</P>
<P>(5) How to distribute the burdens and benefits   of this &quot;social&quot;
economic activity among the   members of the economy.</P>
<P>What distinguishes one kind of economic system from another is how each of
these decisions gets made. What combination of institutional promotion and
conscious human decision making are brought to bear on these decisions? Which
people, or groups of people make which decisions under what kinds of
institutional constraints? Different economic systems answer these questions
differently. And as I argued in the second part of the first week's lecture,
what makes one economic system better or worse than another is whether one makes
these decisions more equitably and efficiently, with a greater degree of
self-management, promoting a greater degree of solidarity and variety, than
another. But what are the major possible economic systems? Feudalism is a system
where peasants manage themselves farming parcels of land to which they have &quot;use
right&quot; by inheritance. But in exchange for their use right they must give
part of their harvest to the Lord of the manor. They might also have to work for
free on lands belonging to the Lord of the manor under their own, or his
supervision. The Lord receives his part of the peasants' produce, and keeps what
the peasants produce on his land supposedly in exchange for protecting the
peasants from conquest by another Lord. But this is very much like store owners
paying protection money to the local mafia who protect them from... you guessed
it, retaliation at the hands of the local mafia should the store owners refuse
or forget to pay protection money. With hindsight, few find the system very
complex. His monopoly of military power permits the Lord to exact tribute in the
form of goods and labor services from those who reside within his fiefdom.
Military power allows the Lord to take part of what the peasants produce, and
consume a great deal more than they without working himself at all.</P>
<P>While it is tempting to agree with Marx that the basis and nature of feudal
exploitation is transparent -- as compared to the nature and basis of capitalist
exploitation -- presumably it did not appear so to many of feudalism's denizens.
One suspects that few Lords saw peasants as other than lazy, cowardly, low life
that didn't deserve the protection he afforded them. And many mixtures of
tradition and religion in different parts of the world have combined to weave
complicated ideological webs of rationalization and acceptance on the part of
peasants who failed to see the distribution of burdens and benefits of feudalism
as anything other than natural, fair, and beyond question.</P>
<P>Markets for goods are not integral to feudalism. [Granted, in real world
feudalism goods were traded between different regions by merchants and artisans
selling to Lords and well-to-do peasants. But this activity was peripheral to
the feudal system -- and eventually proved to be a cancer that contributed to
the demise of feudalism and birth of capitalism.] Nor is there a market for
labor in feudalism. Peasants are not free to sell their services for a wage. The
are precisely unfree to work for anyone, anywhere, because they must work on the
land to which they have inherited user rights and their Lord's lands. Peasants
work under their own direction both on their family plots and usually on the
lands of the Lord as well, so they are not &quot;alienated.&quot; The Lord does
not &quot;oppress&quot; his peasants in the sense that he controls and directs
how they work, but only in the sense that they are his inherited captives who
must render goods and services unto him according to traditions and regulations
that the Lord interprets. And while borrowing and lending occurred in real world
feudalism, a credit market is not integral to feudalism either. Lords would go
into debt to wealthy merchants who operated outside the feudal system to finance
consumption and military binges. But peasants did not borrow to be able to
produce, and pay back principal and interest out of the production thereby made
possible.</P>
<P>In sum, there is exploitation in feudalism, but neither alienation nor
oppression as we defined them in the previous lecture. There are two classes
since peasants work and Lords do not, though Lords consume far better than
peasants. To all of us who can recognize the existence of &quot;feudal
exploitation,&quot; the burdens and benefits of economic cooperation are
distributed unfairly in feudalism with the Lords receiving the lion's share of
the benefits and the peasants shouldering most of the burdens. Nor would one
expect feudalism to be particularly efficient. There is little division of labor
to provide greater productivity. And there is limited incentive for either Lord
or peasant to improve productive techniques since either would have to share a
major part of the gains from any improvement with the other.</P>
<P>Capitalism is an economic system guided by two major economic institutions:
(1) Private ownership of productive assets wherein those who own those assets
hire others to work for them under their direction for an agreed wage [otherwise
known as &quot;private enterprise.&quot; And (2) markets where anyone can buy
and sell any kind of good or service on terms that are mutually acceptable to
buyer and seller [otherwise know as &quot;free markets&quot; or a &quot;market
economy.&quot; So a short hand way of describing a capitalist economy is as a
Private Enterprise Market Economy, or PrEME.</P>
<P>In capitalism there are employers who hire employees to work under their
direction with tools and machinery and land the employers own or have rented.
And there are employees who agree to work under an employer's direction in
return for a wage. Nobody consumes what they produce herself, but instead buy
what they want to consume in goods markets paying with whatever &quot;income&quot;
they may have. Employees, or workers get income from wages. Employers, or
capitalists get income from profits -- the difference between the revenues they
get from selling the goods their employees make and the costs they incur hiring
employees and whatever equipment and materials the employees need to work with.
</P>
<P>Since workers work and capitalists don't, though capitalists consume far
better than workers, there is exploitation in capitalism. But just as few feudal
Lords recognized feudal exploitation, we should not be surprised if few
capitalists recognize capitalist exploitation. Instead most capitalists see
workers as lazy and unable to engage in productive activity if not for the
equipment [capital] and organizational efforts [entrepreneurship] extended by
capitalists. And most capitalists see workers' wages as more than they deserve,
and their own profits as meager compensation for the critical role they play.
More surprisingly many workers fail to see &quot;capitalist exploitation&quot;
and accept the view that since their labor contract is voluntary and mutually
beneficial there is no exploitation. It is also not only capitalists who see
profits as legitimate compensation for an important service -- making available
the equipment and inputs necessary for production and organizing complex
production processes. But for all of us who can recognize &quot;capitalist
exploitation,&quot; the burdens and benefits of economic cooperation are
distributed unfairly in capitalism with capitalists receiving the lion's share
of the benefits and workers shouldering most of the burdens. The basis for
capitalist exploitation is not a monopoly of military power but a monopoly of
the means necessary for production that make it possible for capitalists to pay
workers less than required to purchase all the workers produced, thereby leaving
capitalists with profit income with which to purchase part of what their
employees made without having to work themselves. There is also alienation and
oppression as we have defined them in capitalism since capitalists get to decide
how workers laboring capacities will be utilized.</P>
<P>Strictly speaking, these are the only two classes capitalism &quot;must&quot;
have. But &quot;pure capitalism&quot; seldom exists in reality. Since real
economies evolve in particular historical patterns, there are usually remnants
of previous economic systems within emergent systems, and at some point aspects
of future economic systems begin to develop within present systems. One form
these remnants and precursors take is classes that played important roles in
previous systems or could play important roles in future systems. So during
different eras classes other than capitalists and workers have played important
roles in real world capitalist economies. It is also terribly important to
remember that the organization of the economic sphere of social life is not the
only important defining feature of human societies. How the political, kinship,
and community spheres are organized, how the dynamics in other spheres of social
life affect and are affected by the dynamics in the economic sphere combine with
economic dynamics to determine how a society operates. And besides classes
defined by the dynamics of capitalism (in conjunction with classes from previous
and future economic formations,) groups defined by the social relations in other
spheres -- especially community, gender, and politically defined groups that are
privileged or oppressed by the organization of non-economic activities and
therefore have conflicting interests in social change or stability -- interact
along with whatever classes emerge from the functioning of the economy. These
are important lessons that derive from a complementary holist, as opposed to an
&quot;economistic&quot; perspective. </P>
<P>But even when looking at real world capitalist economies, classes other than
capitalists and workers have played important roles. In early European
capitalism landlords were an important third class, and along with capitalists
and workers were the object of scrutiny by economists like Adam Smith and David
Ricardo in particular. Landlords, or course, were the previously dominant class
in European feudalism and remained a potent force in the European economies as
capitalism developed there. Landlords also play important roles in many third
world economies today. This is not the time or place to discuss how the
introduction of capitalism into third world societies by foreign companies and
governments leads to class and community struggles that are a great deal more
complicated than the class dynamics of some pure, abstract capitalist model.
Suffice it to say that the 500 year evolution of modern day imperialism has left
most third world economies with a much more complex combination of classes and
community groups that struggle over social stability and change in those
societies.</P>
<P>In his own analysis of 19th century European capitalism, Marx focused no
little attention on a class he called the &quot;petite bourgeoisie&quot; of
self-employed sellers of goods and services whose origins were in precapitalist
market dynamics, and who Marx expected to &quot;wither away&quot; with
capitalist development. But elements from this class transformed into part of a
class that has come to play an increasingly important role in modern, corporate
capitalism. Where owners of large corporations are stockholders divorced from
managing the production process, and where mediation of the conflicts between
capitalist and workers both inside and outside the work place has taken on
greater importance, what Mike Albert and I call the coordinator class, and
Barbara and John Ehrenreich call the professional managerial class, play an
important role in the space &quot;between labor and capital.&quot; [Hence the
title of Pat Walker's edited book of essays that discuss how to understand and
evaluate the behavior of this class in modern capitalism.] Moreover, I will
argue that it is impossible to understand what occurred in the &quot;post-capitalist&quot;
economies of the 20th century, or evaluate different post-capitalist visions,
without understanding the coordinator class and its potential to become the
ruling class in particular kinds of post-capitalist economies. But what &quot;post-capitalist&quot;
alternatives exist?</P>
<P>Public Enterprise, Centrally Planned Economies or PuECPEs: In this economic
system control over human-made and natural productive assets is in &quot;public&quot;
rather than &quot;private&quot; hands and the allocation of resources and goods
is determined by a plan. There is no private ownership of land, resources, and
factories giving decision making authority over their use to individuals;
instead authority over the use of &quot;society's productive resources&quot; is
determined by the procedures of &quot;central planning.&quot;</P>
<P>In central planning the relative social values of different final goods and
services is determined by a political process (that may be dictatorial or
democratic) which are then communicated to a Central Planning Board. The CPB is
directed to maximize the value of economic activity in light of the resource
availabilities and productive capabilities of the economy. The CPB collects
information on: the availability of land, resources, and labor with different
skills and training, the technical capabilities of different production
facilities' abilities to combine inputs to produce outputs, and proceeds to
calculates a &quot;plan&quot; that maximizes the social value of production
given resource and technological constraints. How this all can be done, what
different options are available, and the political, social, human, and economic
consequences of how it is done, we will explore theoretically and historically
when we look at the collapse of communism in week seven. For now, suffice it to
say that economies CAN be run according to a central plan that determines what
to produce, how much to produce, how to produce it, and how to distribute it. In
one sense, the planning system consists of communicating society's economic
priorities to planners who determine how best to achieve those goals with
society's limited productive resources. In another sense the planning system
consists of a small group of planners in the CPB and managers in the publicly
owned enterprises deciding what and how to produce things, telling workers where
and how to work, and telling consumers what they will have to consume. While
central planning is essentially a non-market system for making economic
decisions, we will see that markets CAN appear within central planning to
accomplish particular tasks. The important thing when this occurs is to remember
that while markets may be used to distribute goods to consumers once they are
produced, markets do not determine how much of different goods will be produced
in centrally planned economies. Similarly, while labor markets may be used to
assign particular workers to particular enterprises, labor markets do not
determine how many workers of each kind will work in different plants, and do
not determine wage rates. How much to of what to produce and how many workers of
different skills will work where for how much is all determined by the plan even
when markets exist in central planning.</P>
<P>Many supporters of public enterprise, centrally planned economies saw it as
a classless economy. Everyone would be worker/consumers on an equal footing. The
nightmare of private appropriation of scarce social resources along with the
inequity, alienation, and inefficiency this brought would be replaced by a
rational use of productive resources to best achieve society's economic goals.
In this view central planners and managers were merely to be knowledgeable
servants of the workers and consumers, translating their desires about
consumption and work preferences into the most efficient assignment of
productive capabilities. In reality this is not what occurred in the Soviet
Union, Eastern Europe, China, Cuba -- or any place the system has been deployed.
Instead classes emerged in all centrally planned economies -- even the least
corrupt. And I will argue this is predictable, and not merely the result of
non-democratic political influences or betrayals on the part of foolish or
corrupt leaders. Instead of a capitalist ruling class, centrally planned
economies are ruled by a coordinator class of planners and managers who end up
oppressing and exploiting workers and consumers. The idea that the coordinators
are working for the workers and consumers is a doublespeak myth. Instead it is
workers who labor at the behest of the coordinator class who consume more than
ordinary workers, work under more pleasant conditions than ordinary workers, and
make all important economic decisions. Ordinary workers are alienated from
decision making and have inferior work lives and consumption opportunities. This
is not to say that all workers are equally exploited or alienated in centrally
planned systems. And it is important to recognize there are other oppressor and
oppressed groups that emerge from the kind of political, community, and kinship
systems that have accompanied experiments in central planning. But even in at
its best, public enterprise centrally planned economies would be plagued by
classes, exploitation, oppression and alienation. They cannot be classless
utopias.</P>
<P>Public Enterprise Market Economies or PuEMEs: PuEMEs combine public
ownership with allocation of goods and services through markets. We will
consider different variations on this theme in the eighth and ninth week of the
course when we focus on current debates over desirable alternatives to
capitalism. But the most important difference between different &quot;models&quot;
of PuEMEs is how the managers of the public enterprises are selected. In the
early 1950s the Communist Party of Yugoslavia broke with tradition and replaced
its system of central planning with a system they called &quot;workers'
self-managed market socialism.&quot; They not only dismantled their planning
bureaucracy telling public enterprises to buy whatever inputs they needed in the
market place and sell their output in markets; they gave employees considerable
influence over hiring their own enterprise managers. A number of political
economists have elaborated theoretical models based on this idea that I call
Public Enterprise, Employee Managed, Market Economies, PuEEMMEs. The other major
category of PuEME is one where a state agency appoints managers of the publicly
owned enterprises and monitors their performance. A system along these lines was
used in the Soviet Union during the 1920s during what was known as the New
Economic Policy, or NEP. Oscar Lange, Abba Lerner, and Frederick Taylor analyzed
a theoretical version of the model in the 1930s. The model became the &quot;reform
model&quot; critics of the PuECPE model proposed in the Post World War II era in
Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union. And to the extent that &quot;Perestroika&quot;
-- literally economic restructuring -- had specific content in the Gorbachev
era, the idea was to transform to a Public Enterprise, State Managed, Market
Economy, PuESMME.</P>
<P>We will discover there are important differences between PuESMMEs and
PuEEMMEs. But I will argue that while the former is much worse than the latter,
both variants of Public Enterprise Market Economies are inevitably plagued by
exploitation, class divisions, and alienation. In these economies the capitalist
class will also be replaced by a coordinator class who will dominate economic
decision making and exploit ordinary worker/consumers. The systems will be
driven by market enforced competition that promotes self-serving, anti- social
behavior rather than bureaucratic intimidation and patronage that is the motor
force of centrally planned economies, and the dynamics and tendencies of market
based coordinator economies will differ substantially from centrally planned
coordinator economies. But exploitation will certainly exist since public
enterprise market economies necessarily reward participants according to Maxim
2: to each according to the value of his or her personal contribution, which
means those with greater human capital will work in more desirable settings and
enjoy better consumption opportunities than those with less human capital. And a
class of managers, technocrats, bankers, and mutual fund managers -- depending
on the model in question -- will exert an influence over economic decisions
greatly in excess of the degree to which they are affected by the decisions
leaving most workers and consumers alienated from the most important decisions
affecting their economic lives.</P>
<P>Public Enterprise Economies with Participatory Planning, or PuEPPEs: Pat
Devine of the University of Manchester in England has provided a detailed
description of a system of democratic planning he calls negotiated coordination.
Mike Albert and I have presented a model we call participatory economics, or &quot;parecon&quot;
for those familiar with LBBS forums. In both systems enterprises are publicly
owned and market allocation is replaced by a system of democratic, or
participatory planning. As in the case of different versions of PuEMEs there are
important differences between these models, but both claim to remain true to the
goals of those who have insisted that a positive alternative to market driven
systems is both possible and highly desirable.</P>
<P>In a participatory economy enterprises are publicly owned and managed by
workers councils where not only do all members have equal voting rights but job
&quot;complexes&quot; are balanced for both desirability and empowerment.
Consumption opportunities are based on effort, or personal sacrifice, and
consumption is organized by neighborhood consumers councils and federations. And
workers and consumers manage their interconnected activities through a
participatory planning procedure where each workers and consumers council
proposes and revises what its own activity will be in light of increasingly
accurate information about the consequences for others.</P>
<P>There have been no &quot;real world&quot; examples of stable participatory
economies we can study and evaluate. For brief periods revolutionary groups of
workers and activists have engaged in experiments that shed some light on what
we might expect. In the earliest years of the Russian Revolution, before the
Civil War and Bolshevik dictatorship crushed them, factory committees and
soviets attempted to coordinate their economic activities through negotiation
and planning based on solidarity rather than through markets or central
planning. In parts of Northern Italy in the early 1920s, in Anarchist regions of
Spain during the Spanish Civil War, and during the uprising in Hungary in 1956
economic activities were organized for brief periods of time on the many of the
same principals as those that define participatory economics. And there is much
in current Zapatista thinking and practice in Mexico that is consistent with the
ideas behind participatory economics. But historical experience is very limited
and incomplete. In any case, we will spend weeks eight and nine discussing the
debate that has revolved around participatory planning versus market based
alternatives to capitalism over the past four years. But if its advocates are
right, participatory economics goes farther to eliminate exploitation,
oppression, alienation, and class divisions than any of the other economic
systems we know of, and improves efficiency as well. Critics, on the other hand,
have argued that there would be significant efficiency losses as well as
unacceptable losses of personal liberties or freedoms in such economies, and
that a transition to such an economy from a modern capitalist system is
inconceivable. You of course, will read and participate in the debate, and make
up your own minds. </P> 
</BODY></HTML>
