<head>
<title>burns.htm</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#00FFFF">
<p><a href="96zmi.htm"><img src="96logo.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=160 height=140></a></p>
<p><img src="spkout.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32>There is a change in the discourse on healthcare in Canada toward increasing discussion of 
privatization of parts of the public system. This has emerged recently and is taking place in the 
media but also within the leadership of professional organizations. The debate is fostered by the 
notion that the public system is no longer viable given the perceived need for decreased government 
spending to help curb the national debt, rhetoric that closely parallels what is being spouted south of 
the border. There is general acceptance of this thinking, which has framed the debate along 
right-wing lines, despite the strong evidence that single-payer healthcare administered by 
government has proven to be a much more cost-efficient system than what currently exists in the 
US.</p>
<p>The single-payer debate that was lost badly in the US a few years ago provided Canadians with a 
lot of cross-border propaganda that did nothing to improve the perception of the Canadian system 
within Canada. Managed care is emerging as the dominant system in the US and has so far proved 
to be extremely profitable . Expansion into the Canadian market would be the logical next step . 
The development of a two-tiered system such as exists in the UK will undermine services in the 
public system and bring an end to universality based on equal quality of services. It is my hope to 
increase the amount of discussion about this possibility and to bring a greater sense of urgency to it. 
I suspect that the groundwork is currently being laid to allow US managed care companies to enter 
the Canadian market and, if action isn't taken to open the debate now, that it will be too late to take 
any preventive action. I am interested in networking with other individuals to plan a strategy for 
public education around this issue.</p>
<hr>
<h4 align=left>--Michael Burns</h4>
<p><a href="96con.htm">Back to ZMI 1996 Contacts</a></p>
</body>

