<head>
<title>jamison.htm</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#00FF40">
<p><a href="96zmi.htm"><img src="96logo.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=160 height=140></a> <img src="spkout.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32>June 14, 1996 <strong>SOAP-BOXING on THE WEB</strong></p>
<hr>
<h3>The State of Israel and the People of Palestine </h3>
<p>&quot;Israel's actions aren't terrorism&quot; is the title of a commentary by Norman Miller that was printed in 
the Ashland (Oregon) Daily Tidings, May 21, 1996. The text follows:</p>
<p>&quot;The commentary by Robert Jones on the April 23 Opinion page is definitely Palestinian sour 
grapes. Israel's closing of the West Bank and Gaza borders following Arab terrorism has been 
going on since 1967. The Arab population in these two areas had hidden the terrorists from Israeli 
police, and continue to do so, forcing Israeli action.</p>
<p>&quot;You mistakenly refer to police attempts to arrest these murderers as terrorism. These are the same 
as the Montana and Oklahoma acts, and are vile attempts to frighten the legitimate government.</p>
<p>&quot;In 1948, the Israeli government offered the Arabs living within the U.N.-mandated boundaries the 
opportunity to become citizens, to live and work in Israel. Many did, and do not collaborate with 
Palestinian terrorism.</p>
<p>&quot;The other Arabs were offered sanctuary at that time by Egypt, Syria and Jordan, who encouraged 
them not to accept the Israeli offer. They were not given citizenship in these Arab countries, but 
were declared refugees for economic and political reasons.</p>
<p>&quot;You said the terrorist's families did not know about their acts. That's a lie. Arab families are not 
American. They back their family all the way, and terrorism attempts have been continuing for 30 
years from these same family groups.</p>
<p>&quot;The Arab refugees who migrated to Egypt and Jordan in 1948 were not permitted to work, and 
were placed by their brethren in refugee camps in Gaza and the West Bank, and were supported 
by U.N. grants.</p>
<p>&quot;When Israel signed the peace treaty with Egypt and returned the Sinai, Egypt refused to take back 
the Gaza strip, a piece of Sinai. Jordan has also refused to take back the West Bank. These 
Palestinians had been the major obstacle to peace treaties with these countries. Both Egypt and 
Jordan treaties specifically excluded the Palestinian refugees because they didn't want to support 
them.</p>
<p>&quot;Both Gaza and the West Bank do not have jobs for their people. Since 1967, Israel has been the 
only country to permit these people to work in their land-even though they are not citizens. In 
addition to giving them Israeli jobs, the Israeli government established schools in Gaza and the 
West Bank, giving them education for the first time, and built utilities and housing, which never 
existed before in these areas. The Israeli government did these things to improve Arab's quality of 
life.</p>
<p>&quot;For your information, the Hezbollah terrorists, supported by Islamic populations of Lebanon, Syria 
and Iran, have been bombing Israel for more than 20 years. They live and fire their bombs from 
outside their homes. This is war, supported or not, by the Lebanese government.</p>
<p>&quot;Arab propaganda frequently excludes facts. The above were missed by your comments. It is 
common knowledge that Israel never acts without sufficient cause, because they have always lived 
under the world's microscope.&quot;</p>
<hr>
<p><strong>TO RESPOND:</strong></p>
<p>Palestinian &quot;terrorists&quot; are Israeli-made, as the Jewish resistance in Warsaw was Nazi-made. 
People are not born terrorists. Terrorism could be violence in resistance to authority; usually it's 
violence for the purpose of subjugation. Blowing up the Oklahoma City Federal Building was &quot; the 
same&quot; as Palestinian's resistance to Israel's encroachment on their homeland, asserts Miller: an 
ideological flight from rationality. Miller refers to UN mandated boundaries of Israel, but who gave 
the UN authority to give away the land where the Palestinians lived? Actually, under the semblance 
of law the UN action was a disguise for U. S.-British seizure and disposal of foreign land. By way 
of the &quot;Balfour Declaration&quot; it sanctioned British betrayal of their Arab allies of the first World War, 
who had been promised Arab political suzerainty of Palestine, instead authorizing a Jewish-Zionist 
state in Arab territory. No more appropriate label for this piece of imperial treachery could be 
imagined; Arthur James, First Earl of Balfour, was nicknamed &quot;Bloody Balfour&quot; for his style of 
implementing Britannia's imperial fiats in the countries of various subjugated people of the empire 
that bestrode the seven seas.</p>
<p>The U. S. also approved of this gift of the expropriated heritage of the Palestinians to another 
people; its ruling class had built a nation by similar practices. For one thing it helped ease the 
problems of domestic anti-Semitism. (Considering what the Jews have endured, we should 
remember, ironically , that Palestinians are of Semitic origin , too.) It also facilitated accomplishment 
of the U. S. aim of giving military-political support to U. S.-based corporations lusting for a hold on 
the newly discovered oil wealth of the middle east.. What an equitable division! One interloper, the 
new state, got a choice portion of surface ground; the other, in the course of time, a lion's share of 
what lay underneath. Thus was more than half of Palestine handed over to the theocratic control of 
Zionism; at the time the Jewish population, despite the British-U.S. facilitated influx of Jewish 
refugees, was considerably less than 50% of the total population of the territory. With the UN fig 
leaf in place, the Zionists sent agents such as Golda Meir to the U. S. to solicit money to buy arms 
for use in a campaign of forthright collectivized terror to drive the indigenous people out of the new 
imperially decreed state.</p>
<p>Israel conducted a similar program after 1967 in the areas the mandate had reserved, nominally, it 
turned out, for the Palestinians; who soon learned that Turkish despotism had been gentle in 
comparison to Zionist settler-state occupation. Much of its energy of the state of Israel since its 
artificial conception has been directed towards seizing Palestinian land and rendering uninhabitable 
whatever fragmented portion of original, historical Palestine remains to the Palestinians. Miller 
excuses Israel's policy of mass punishment for deeds it declares to be terrorism, on the grounds that 
the Palestinian people generally are complicit in the actions of individual Palestinians. To deny this, 
he says flatly, is a &quot;lie&quot; -- thus appearing to approve of Israel's de facto position that ethnic identity 
can itself be criminal.</p>
<p>Although, with the heralded &quot;peace process,&quot; official bigotry is partially muted these days, Israel's 
recent action in sealing its borders to all Palestinians after terroristic exchanges in which many more 
Palestinians and other Arab people died than Israelis suggests the change of tone is propaganda, 
simply. &quot;Israel's actions aren't terrorism.&quot;(!) Uprooting Palestinian's orchards; stealing their water? 
Destroying their communities and economy? Establishing settler enclaves in the remnant areas, i. e., 
what is left of the lands the UN mandate reserved for Palestinians, under guard of Jewish vigilantes 
and the Israeli Defense Forces? Destroying their indigenous means of existence, to render them 
dependent on the Israeli economy for low-wage employment, then imposing 24-hour curfews on 
them <em>en masse</em> for weeks at a time? Locking up thousands of Palestinian youth in desert prison 
camps? Such actions are not terrorism! But &quot;the Israeli government established schools in Gaza and 
the West Bank, giving them [the Palestinians] education for the first time, and built utilities and 
housing...&quot; Yes, no doubt the Palestinians did get an education.</p>
<p>Israel has &quot;always lived under the world's microscope,&quot; the commentary concludes. But the world 
apparently has been asleep. Where the settler whites failed, finally, to establish a color-based 
apartheid state in South Africa, the settler-Zionists succeeded, so it seems, and we have 
religio-ethnic apartheid: an &quot;ultra&quot; variety in the West Bank and Gaza strip, since South Africa's 
material provision for the bantustans was superior to Israel's for the occupied territories; &quot;quasi&quot; for 
the Palestinians in Israel proper since although granted citizenship they are systematically 
persecuted otherwise.</p>
<p>Still, when all is said and done, focus on Israel as a perpetrator of terrorism is too narrow. 
Terrorism is stock in trade for most countries, and the one with the greatest means practices it on a 
vaster scale. No need to elaborate on the record of the U. S. in making the world safe from such 
infernal threats as Grenada, Cuba, Panama, Nicaragua, Iraq -- not looking back to such ancient 
history as the racial cleansing out of Native Americans and the first great economic enterprise of 
Europe-in-America: the enslavement of Africans, the slave trade, and the super-exploitation of 
slave labor in creation of the new-model capitalist economy.</p>
<p>Mr. Miller: our world here in the USA is sustained by terror. One essential for reducing terrorism is 
to lessen reliance of our government and society on the weapons of terror: nuclear weapons, 
armaments of all kinds, armies, police, prisons, the apparatus of coercion used domestically and 
internationally, and, maybe most importantly, our slavish dependence on the labor of others. Yes, it 
will entail radical change in our government, law, and society. But we can begin.</p>
<hr>
<p><font size=3><strong>--Hal Jamison</strong></font><br>
Board member, Jackson County (Oregon) Human Rights Commission<br>
<a href="mailto:harburjam@jeffnet.org"><strong>harburjam@jeffnet.org</strong></a></p>
