<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "+//ISBN 82-7640-037::WWW//DTD HTML//EN//2.0" "html.dtd">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Power and Prospects</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><IMG SRC="header.gif" ALIGN="TOP">
<HR>
<H1><A NAME="Powerandprospects">Powers and Prospects</A></H1>  
<IMG SRC="powers.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
<H2>
Reflections on Human Nature and the Social Order</H2>
<H3>By Noam Chomsky</H3>
<P>In this wide-ranging intellectual tour de force, Noam Chomsky  brings
together his thoughts on topics ranging from language and human nature, to the
Middle East settlement and the role of East Timor in the New World Order. This
is the first collection of his essays in recent years to bring together
questions of philosophy, ethics, and foreign policy, and he includes his first
published remarks on political goals and visions.   </P>
<P>This book will be of great interest to both the general reader who is new to
Chomsky's political and linguistic work, and the avid Chomsky reader who will
discover new writing on current topics. It includes concise essays that explain
Chomsky's philosophical approach to linguistics and offer a short history of the
study of language; describe the role of the &quot;cognitive revolution&quot; in
linguistics; and explore the way scientific questions are asked, answered, and
influenced by dominant ways of thinking.  Essays on the intellectual
responsibilities of writers and on Chomsky's own political goals and visions
provide a bridge from his chapters on human nature to four strong pieces on
issues in international affairs.</P>
<P>Whether he is looking at the Middle East, the relationship of Democracy and
markets in the New World Order, or human rights violations in East Timor,
Chomsky draws links between foreign policy decisions, the state of intellectual
culture, the role of the media, and the potential for free and democratic
societies to understand and counter the heinous acts being committed in their
name. Chomsky's refreshingly clear views of the world and the nature of things
are supported by a wealth of detail.</P>
<P><I>A world renowned linguist and outspoken critic of U.S. foreign policy
and the mass media, Noam Chomsky has served as Institute Professor of the
Department of Linguistics and Philosophy at MIT. According to the Arts and
Humanities Citation Index, Chomsky was cited as a source more often than any
other living scholar between 1980 and 1992. He has published nine books with
South End Press.</I></P>
<P>$16.00 paper, $40.00 cloth</P>
<HR>
