<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>FBI Secrets</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="header.gif" ALIGN="TOP">
<HR>
<H1><A NAME="CriminalINjustice">Criminal Injustice</A></H1>  
<IMG SRC="criminal.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
<HR>
<H2>
Confronting the Prison Crisis</H2>
<H3>Edited by Elihu Rosenblatt</H3>
<P>Politicians and the mass media have recently ushered in an enormous wave of
fear about violent crime. Meanwhile, the reality of the criminal prosecution
system remains carefully hidden from public understanding by the same
individuals and institutions in big business and government who manufacture
consent and engineer mass culture. 
</P>
<P>This remarkable anthology, edited by the coordinator of the Prison Activist
Resource Center (PARC), takes the discussion of crime out of the realm of false
debate fostered by an increasingly conservative and punitive state, and exposes
the economic and political realities behind the imprisonment of astounding
numbers of the working class, working poor, and people of color. 
</P>
<P>
The popular obsession with crime serves as a smokescreen to divert our attention
and energies from confronting the underlying causes for increasing violence in
our society. Criminal Injustice argues that we must counter the mythology of
crime hype by exposing and educating against the real dangers people face, such
as poverty, police abuse, and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>As thorough as it is insightful, this book examines issues ranging from the
role of prisons in the repression of activists to the health crisis behind bars.
It discusses women in prison, the death penalty, the rise of maximum security
control units, and political prisoners and prisoners of war. 
</P>
<P>The contributors are articulate commentators on U.S. social, political, and
economic realities who provide important statistics and cogent analyses which
are accessible to the general reader and essential to scholars and activists.
</P>
<P>Prisons can be seen as a barometer for all that is ill at the core of our
society. Thus, academics in the fields of Sociology, African-American Studies,
or Political Science, as well as organizers working around issues as diverse as
environmental justice, housing, or reproductive rights will find this tremendous
resource indispensable in informing, inspiring, and providing direction for
action. 
</P>
<P>$18.00 paper, $40.00 cloth</P>
<HR>
<MENU>
