<H1>Welcome to the Web!</H1>
</CENTER>

<p>If you are new to the World Wide Web, <b>don't be intimidated!</b> The
Web is simply a
large number of pages of text and graphics that are linked together with
<b>hyperlinks</b>.
Most browsers (the programs you use to navigate the Web) indicate that
an element of text is a hyperlink by underlining it (as in the link:
<a href="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</a>).
And many graphic elements (if your browser displays them) are also links.
Graphical browsers, like Netscape and Microsoft Explorer, allow you to
follow links just by clicking on them with the mouse. Text based browsers,
like Lynx, let you follow links using your keyboard. Don't worry about
clicking on links you're not sure of -- you can't cause any harm to the
Web.

<p>Although the easiest way to learn is by doing, here is a list of some
links to starting points for learning more about browsing. Whenever you
click on a link you will go to the associated site. You can always come
back here by using the back up a page option or the Return to Home option
on your browser.

<ul>
<li><b><a href="http://www.yahoo.com/text/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/
Information_and_Documentation/Beginner_s_Guides/">Internet Beginner's Guides</a>

<li><a href="http://www.eit.com/web/www.guide/">A Guide to Cyberspace</a></b>
</ul>

<p>If you want to create your own web pages or create your own site, you
need to understand a little about the underlying language of Web design.
Here are some good places to begin:</p>

<ul>
<li><b><a href="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/General/Internet/WWW/HTMLPrimer.html">A
Beginner's Guide to HTML</a>

<li><a href="http://home.netscape.com/assist/net_sites/index.html">Creating
Net Sites</a>

<li><a href="http://www-slis.lib.indiana.edu/Internet/programmer-page.html">A
Primer for creating Web Resources</a></b>
</ul>

<HR WIDTH=20% SIZE=3>


<a name="C1"> </a>

<h2 align=center>Starting Points For Web Surfing</h2>

<p>There are two basic ways to travel the Web. You can have something in
mind that you want to find and use a search engine to look for related
sites and pages. Or you can browse by going to a site with lots of interesting
links and following those that strike your fancy, then continuing to new
links, and so on. Here we give you a start with both these approaches by
indicating:

<CENTER>
<P><TABLE>
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=25%>
<CENTER><b>Good Sites To Search From:</b></CENTER>

<ul>
<li><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</A>

<li><A HREF="http://www.excite.com/">Excite</A>

<li><A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">Alta Vista</A>

<li><A HREF="http://www.opentext.com/">OpenText</A>

<li><A HREF="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</A>

<li><A HREF="http://www.webcrawler.com/">WebCrawler</A>
</ul>

<TD valign=top WIDTH=25%>
<CENTER><b>Good Sites To Start Browsing From:</b></CENTER>

<ul>
<li><A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</A>

<li><A HREF="http://www.shareworld.com/">ShareWorld</A>

<li><A HREF="http://www.igc.apc.org/">The Progressive Directory at IGC</A>

<li><a href="http://www.webactive.com/webactive/">WebActive</a>
</ul>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<HR WIDTH=20% SIZE=3>


<a name="C2"> </a>

<center>
<P><font size=4><I>Left On Line's Guide to</I></font>
<h2>Left Links</h2>
</center>

<p align=center><font SIZE=-1>This list focuses on Left-oriented
publications and activist resources. Many of these sites were culled from
<a href="http://www.webactive.com/webactive/"><b>WebActive</b></a> and <a
href="http://www.igc.apc.org/"><b>IGC</b></a> sites.</font>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=45%>
<DL>

<dt><a href="http://mxe115.rh.psu.edu/index.htm">Action Center Homepage</a>
<dd>Billed as an &quot;activists' center for training in organizing and
networking,&quot; it is a collection of very good material (plus some
links) to aid the progressive activist.

<dt><a href="http://hoshi.cic.sfu.ca/adbusters/">Adbusters' Culture
Jammers Headquarters</a>
<dd>A great site done by Adbusters, a group that fights fire with fire. See
their ads that fly in the face of billion dollar images.

<dt><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com">The Atlantic</a>
<dd>Since 1857, the Atlantic has provided intellectual
coverage of politics, society, culture and the arts. The magazine, which
falls somewhere between the Nation and Harpers, presents a Web site full
of its writing, and now offers the Election Connection.

<dt><a href="http://MediaFilter.org/MFF/CAQ_Contents.html">CovertAction
Quaterly </a>
<dd>CovertAction Quarterly is a publication devoted
to human rights and uncovering covert activity.

<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/crossroads/">Crossroads</a>
<dd>A magazine aimed at rebuilding an effective left political current in
U.S. politics. Published by the <a
href="http://www.igc.apc.org/crossroads/ises.html">Institute for Social and
Economic Studies</a>.

<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/dollars/">Dollars & Sense</a>
<dd>A magazine that explains the workings of the U.S. and international
economies and provides left persepctives on current economic affairs.

<dt><a href="http://www.earthisland.org/">Earth Island Institute</a>
<dd>Run by feisty environmentalists, Earth Island Institute
has a site which includes full-text newsletters, and information on thirty
projects related to everything from from dolphin, whales and sea turtles
to environmental justice to rethinking paper.

<dt><a href="http://www.essential.org/EI.html">Essential Information</a>
<dd>Founded by Ralph Nader, EI provides provocative information to the
public on important topics neglected by the mass media and policy makers.

<dt><a href="http://www.fair.org/fair/">Fairness and Accuracy in
Reporting </a>
<dd>FAIR documents media bias towards corporations
and their insensitivity to the interests of labor, women, minorities, and
other public interest groups.

<dt><a href="http://iww.org/">IWW Resource</a>
<dd>The site of the International
Workers of the World. It contains everything from information about the
IWW to links related to Earth First! and the striking journalists of the
Detroit News.

<dt><a href="http://www.bypass.com/~N_E_Research/left/">Jay's
Leftist and &quot;Progressive&quot; Internet Resources Directory </a>
<dd>Wow! Jay has put together quite a list, and it is well organized. It's
enough
to keep you busy for weeks.

<dt><a href="http://www.channel1.com/users/jay/welcome.htm">Madness</a>
<dd>Madness is a group of politically-minded twentysomethings who present
episodic,
subversive fiction. The result is, well, Madness.

<TD valign=top WIDTH=45%>

<DL>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.org/MakingContact/">Making Contact</a>
<dd>A new national radio program that gives listeners information they need
to take action. It is produced by Norman Solomon and David Barsamian.

<dt><a href="http://www.mojones.com/">The MoJo Wire </a>
<dd>The MoJo Wire is Mother Jones Magazine's interactive WWW publication.
The MoJo Wire offers
a feast of information for progressives.

<dt><a href="http://www.thenation.com/">The Nation </a>
<dd>No need to browse the news stand for The Nation, for it is always in
the same place
on the Web. Feast on the digital edition of this hard-hitting progressive
publication.

<dt><a href="http://www.pacifica.org/">Pacifica </a>
<dd>Balance your Pacifica listening with some Pacifica reading. This site
serves mostly to inform you of the organization, its mission and its
contents. There are some listening options, including out-takes of an
interview with Noam Chomsky.

<dt><a href="http://www.ran.org/ran/">Rainforest Action Network </a>
<dd>RAN is a decade old organization dedicated to protecting rainforests
and the rights of the people who work in them. The RAN web page is
exquisitely designed, but may be rough on 14.4k modem users.

<dt><a href="http://www.seac.org/">SEAC</a>
<dd>Website for the Student Environmental Action Coalition, with over 1,500
high school and college groups in all fifty states.

<dt><a href="http://www.socialpolicy.org/">Social Policy</a>
<dd>A quarterly magazine that address politics, culture and
&quot;movements.&quot; Stylish yet simple layout and diverse content.

<dt><a href="http://www.lglobal.com/TAO/">The Media Collective</a>
<dd>A rich collection of anarchist resources

<dt><a href="http://www.utne.com/">The Utne Lens</a>
<dd>The Utne Lens is the Utne Reader's online publication.

<dt><a href="http://www.webactive.com/">WebActive</a>
<dd>Your weekly source on progressive activism online.</a>

<dt><a href="http://www.lbbs.org/zmag/index.htm">Z Magazine</a>
<dd>Z Magazine is a provocative alternative monthly magazine which boasts
Noam Chomsky among its frequent contributors.

<dt><a href="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</a>
<dd>Your starting point for such valuable resources as the <A
href="http://www.worldmedia.com/archive/">Noam Chomsky Archive</a>, <a
href="http://www.lbbs.org/zmag.index.htm">Z Magazine</a>, the Left On Line
Bulletin Board System, Left On Line University and the Z Media Institute.

</TABLE>

<HR WIDTH=20% SIZE=3>


<a name="C3"> </a>

<h2 align=center>Some Interesting Places To Visit</h2>

<p align=center><font SIZE=-1>These sites were culled from the much larger
list available at the <a
href="http://www.webactive.com/webactive/"><b>WebActive</b></a>
site.</font>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP>
<DL>
<dt><a href="http://www.cais.com/agm/">The Abortion Rights Activist Home
Page</a>
<dd>The Abortions Rights Activist Home Page is a new and evolving site
intended to provide information to the pro-choice community.

<dt><a href="http://www.ns.doe.ca//aeb/ssd/Acid/acidFAQ.html">Acid Rain FAQ</a>
<dd>The Acid Rain FAQ comes courtesy of Environment Canada's A Primer on
Environmental Citizenship.

<dt><a href="http://www.aflcio.org">AFL-CIO</a>
<dd>The AFL-CIO web site hosts information about the AFL-CIO and resources
valuable to anyone interested in labor.

<dt><a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/race/aanews">African
American News Service</a>
<dd>The African American News Service is sponsored
by the Institute for Global Communications and serves as an alternative
source for news relating to the African American community.

<dt><a href="http://www.anc.org.za/">African National Congress Home
Page</a>
<dd>The African National Congress has a stunning web site complete with
links to other South African resources.

<dt><a href="http://www.aclu.org">American Civil Liberties Union</a>
<dd>The American Civil Liberties Union has taken the
Web by storm with its Freedom Network. There's too much to describe here.
Just go there and spend a day or two.

<dt><a href="http://www.apn.com/">American Political Network</a>
<dd>Do you want to get &quot;virtually&quot; inside
the Beltway? Then the APN is the place to be. Such offerings as The Hotline,
American Healthline, and Greenwire, each offered daily, will ensure that
you never miss a beat.

<dt><a href="http://www.io.org/amnesty/">Amnesty International Online</a>
<dd>Amnesty International is now on the web. Among
the site's highlights: AI's 1994 country reports, details on current Amnesty
projects, and links to other human rights resources on the Internet.

<dt><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/index.html">Animal Rights
Resource Site</a>
<dd>The Animal Rights Resource Site maintains a wealth
of information about animal rights ... the photos are not for children.

<dt><a href="http://www.enews.com:80/magazines/body/">Body Politic</a>
<dd>Body Politic is a pro-choice magazine ironically
based in Binghamton, New York -- the birthplace of Operation Rescue. Its
web site offers gopher access to some articles as well as information on
subscribing.

<dt><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/">The Body Shop</a>
<dd>The business of the Body Shop is the manufacture
and retail of beauty products. At the same time, the Body Shop is concerned
with being a good citizen of the world. The Body Shop's Web site currently
focuses on the latter task...

<dt><a href="http://www.cais.com/agf/cwindex.htm">Catholic Worker Home Page</a>
<dd>This is an unofficial page done by an admirer of
the Catholic Worker movement. The movement, born during the Great
Depression, aims to provide food, clothing, shelter and welcome the needy
in poor areas, both urban and rural.

<dt><a href="http://latino.sscnet.ucla.edu/">Chicano/Latino Network</a>
<dd>The Chicano/Latino Network (CLNet), is a &quot;general
Latino focused Internet site serving all segments of the community.&quot;
It is based at UCLA and offers a wide variety of information, ranging from
resources for academic research on Latino issues to job listings.

<dt><a href="http://www.dnai.com/~children/">Children Now </a>
<dd>Children Now is a non-partisan non-profit organization
dedicated to protecting the rights and welfare of children.

<dt><a href="http://www.cpsr.org/home.html">Computer Professionals
for Social Responsibility </a>
<dd>CPSR, which recently revamped its web site, is
a non-profit organization concerned with the effects of computers on society.
Of particular interest on the CPSR home page is a page of articles about
gender issues and computing.

<dt><a href="http://www.essential.org/CMEP/">Critical Mass Energy
Project </a>
<dd>Promotes energy conservation and tracks government
activities related to such issues as nuclear power, radioactive waste,
renewable energy and fuel efficiency.

<dt><a href="http://www.dsausa.org/">Democratic Socialists of America</a>
<dd>The largest socialist organization in the United States, and the
principal U.S. affiliate of the Socialist International.

<dt><a href="http://www.doonesbury.com/">The Doonesbury Electronic
Town Hall </a>
<dd>Doonesbury, the witty and poignant cartoon by Gary
Trudeau, has arrived on the Web and it has a mission. In addition to daily
political information, flashbacks to historic news and Doonesbury cartoons,
the site hosts a section called Get Involved.

<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/econet/">EcoNet @igc</a>
<dd>EcoNet is a large directory of environmental sites, maintained by the
Institute for Global Communications.

<dt><a href="http://www.eff.org/">Electronic Frontier Foundation</a>
<dd>EFF is a leading non-profit civil liberties organization
working in the public interest to protect privacy, free expression, and
access to online resources and information.

<dt><a href="http://www.envirolink.org/issues/esa/">Endangered Species
Act On-Line Resource Guide </a>
<dd>The Endangered Species Act is a critical, controversial
and confusing piece of legislation that serves to prevent human actions
from pushing animals and plants into extinction. The on-line resource guide
is a one-stop shop for information about the Act, and it encourages you
to play a part in preventing the Act from following the route of the dodo
and the passenger pigeon.

<dt><a href="http://www.edf.org">Environmental Defense Fund </a>
<dd>EDF is a non-profit organization which aims to
stop environmental pollution by encouraging business, labor, government,
and citizen groups to cooperate and identify practical policies to protect
the environment.

<dt><a href="http://www.enviroindustry.com/">Environmental Industry</a>
<dd>This site hosts information on businesses that
provide environmental products and/or services. It lists companies,
organizations
and publications. It also includes a calendar of related events.

<dt><a href="http://www.webdirectory.com/">The Environmental Organization
WebDirectory </a>
<dd>If you went to one of this directory's listed sites every day, you'd
finish in about three years.

<dt><a href="http://www.ewg.org/">Environmental Working Group</a>
<dd>The EWG is a project of the Tides Foundation. The
site serves to distribute the organization's reports on such subjects as
pesticides, pollution and farm subsidies.

<dt><a href="http://www.feminist.org/">The Feminist Majority Foundation</a>
<dd>The Feminist Majority heads to the Net with the
Women's Web World, a site packed with information and calls for action,
all pertaining to promoting a women's rights.

<TD VALIGN=TOP>

<DL>
<dt><a href="http://www.feminist.com/">Feminist.Com</a>
<dd>The richness of the tree that greets the visitor
to this site is an indication of the resources presented within. Let
Feminist.com
guide you to health information, activism and much more.

<dt><a href="http://www.gdn.org/">Global Democracy Network</a>
<dd>A searchable stockpile of documents related to
international human rights. Though human rights issues is the focus of
this site, it also includes links to governmental information of nearly
30 nations.

<dt><a href="http://www.greenpeace.org/">Greenpeace International</a>
<dd>This is the official WWW site of Greenpeace, and it's looking better
and better.

<dt><a href="http://www.house.gov/democrats/welcome.html">House Democrats
Home Page </a>
<dd>Rep. Richard Gephardt, Democratic minority leader,
has established the House Democrats Home Page which offers updates on current
legislation, profiles of Democratic leaders, and press releases.

<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/hr/">Human Rights @igc</a>
<dd>This web page, hosted by the Institute for Global
Communications, includes information related to US and international human
rights.

<dt><a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org/11/headlines">IGC's News
Headlines </a>
<dd>The gopher site of the Institute for Global Communications
maintains news headlines and articles on topics not normally covered by
the mainstream press.

<dt><a href="http://www.alternet.org/an/">Institute for Alternative
Journalism</a>
<dd>An organization based in San Francisco that is an &quot;advocate for
diversity of news
opinions and analysis within the media.&quot;

<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/">The Institute for Global
Communications</a>
<dd>IGC links together
different elements of the progressive community through communications
technology. </a>

<dt><a href="http://www.isoc.org/">The Internet Society </a>
<dd>As described on the site, &quot;The Internet Society is a non
governmental International organization for global cooperation and
coordination for the Internet and its internetworking technologies and
applications. &quot;

<dt><a href="http://www.zen.org/~brendan/kids.html">The Kids on the
Web </a>
<dd>This site includes seemingly-endless links to locations on the 'Net related
to kids. Games, books and educational resources abound. All ages will have
fun and learn. </a>

<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/labornet/">LaborNet </a>
<dd>LaborNet
is one of the five networks of the <a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/">Institute
for Global Communications</a>.

<dt><a href="http://www.lbbs.org/lolu.htm">Left On Line University</a>
<dd>The Left On Line University (LOLU) &quot;provides three semesters per
year of university
level, 15-week courses in political, social, economic, historical, and
activist topics.&quot; Noam Chomsky, Holly Sklar, and Howard Zinn are among
LOLU's faculty.

<dt><a href="http://www.loc.gov/">Library of Congress Information
Services</a>
<dd>This is the WWW resource of the Library of Congress.

<dt><a href="http://www.bluemarble.net/~mitch/groups.html">Mitch's
Environmental Action Page</a>
<dd>Mitch has compiled a wonderful assortment of action items and information on
dioxins, PCBs, other toxics, as well as general environmental issues.

<dt><a href="http://www.politicalindex.com">The National Political
Index</a>
<dd>A new addition to political archives and indices. But this one could
soon become the definitive list.

<dt><a href="http://www.npr.org">National Public Radio </a>
<dd>NPR's web site offers
information about NPR and newsheadlines in RealAudio format. (Note: you
can access NPR audio over the Internet daily at the <a href="http://www.RealAudio.com">RealAudio</a> web site.)</a>

<dt><a href="http://ukanaix.cc.ukans.edu/~marc/native_main.html">NativeWeb </a>
<dd>NativeWeb maintains resources about native peoples as well as links to
other relevant sites.

<dt><a href="http://www.newparty.org/">The New Party </a>
<dd>The New Party is just what the name implies. It is a progressive
alternative to the two-party system, promoting an agenda that includes
campaign finance reform, improving public schools, universal voter
registration, creating family supporting jobs without wrecking the
environment, raising the minimum wage and universal access to health care.
For now it is focusing on local offices, but it has high hopes.

<dt><a href="http://www.outnow.com">OutNOW! Alive </a>
<dd>One of the best gay sites and publications available on the Net. Its
excellent contents provides a unifying force for the highly-dispersed gay
community.

<dt><a
href="gopher://gopher.brown.edu:70/11/brown/studinfo/studact/oxfam/hungorg/o
xfam">Oxfam
</a>
<dd>Since 1970, Oxfam America has been working with poor people throughout
the world to combat hunger.

<dt><a href="http://www.peacenet.apc.org/peacenet/">PeaceNet @igc</a>
<dd>PeaceNet is a world-wide computer network &quot;serving organizations
and individuals working for positive change in the area of peace.&quot;
PeaceNet is maintained by the Insitute for Global Communications. </a>

<dt><a href="http://www.politicsusa.com/">PoliticsUSA </a>
<dd>Election 96 is coming! Watch it unfold on PoliticsUSA. Daily news,
campaign analyses and a rundown of candidates' positions on key issues.

<dt><a href="http://www.prognet.com/prognet/">Progressive Networks,
Inc.</a>
<dd>Progressive Networks is the creator of RealAudio audio-on-demand
software for the Internet. In addition to RealAudio, PN aims to bring the
networking power of the Internet to bear on social and political issues. PN
is the sponsor of What's New in Activism Online.

<dt><a href="http://www.rednet.co.uk:80/redpepper/">Red Pepper </a>
<dd>Red Pepper Magazine brings the UK's cultural and political left to you.

<dt><a href="http://www.clark.net/pub/jeffd/index.html">The Right
Side of the Web </a>
<dd>The Right Side of the Web is one of the most popular conservative sites
on the World Wide Web.

<dt><a href="http://www.sierraclub.org">Sierra Club </a>
<dd>The Sierra Club web site offers information on the Sierra Club, its
local chapters, and action alerts.

<dt><a href="http://www.house.gov/mbr_dir/membr_dir.html">U.S. House
of Representatives - Member Directory</a>
<dd>The U.S. House of Representatives member directory allows you to easily
find out who your representatives are and how to contact them.

<dt><a href="http://www.ucsusa.org/">Union of Concerned Scientists</a>
<dd>Good science usually speaks the truth. The Union of Concerned
Scientists gathers the best science in order to defend peace and
environmental protection.

<dt><a href="http://www.well.com/">The WELL</a>
<dd>Be sure to take a trip to The WELL. Its <a
href="http://www.well.com/Community/">community pages</a> and its <a
href="http://gopher.well.com:70/">gopher server</a> offer a fantastic
wealth of links and information. While you are there, check out the <A
HREF=" http://gopher.well.sf.ca.us:70/1s/Politics/activist.tools">Activist
Toolkit</a>.

<dt><a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/">White House</a>
<dd>This is Bill Clinton's home.</a>

<dt><a href="http://www.wald.com/">Working Assets Long Distance </a>
<dd>Working Assets Long Distance provides long-distance telephone service
and contributes a portion of its revenue to progressive non-profits.

</TABLE>

