<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>LOL Guide: Other Internet Tools</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#3A0D9F" vlink="#AF0475" alink="#0E7F09">

<h1 align=center>Other Internet Tools</h1>

<P>The World Wide Web is only one of the many services available on LOL and
the Internet. Perhaps you've already used <b>e-mail</b> (electronic mail),
which lets you send and receive information to and from anyone on WOL or
the Internet. But while e-mail and the web are the most popular Internet
applications, there are several other tools that come in handy from time to
time.

<a name="n"> </a>
<P><b>Newsgroups</b> are global discussion forums covering all sorts of
topics, including computers, recreation, science, social issues, and an
innumerable number of other subjects. <i>Usenet,</i> the system that
carries the newsgroups, uses a hierarchical naming scheme. For example, all
the newsgroups relating to social issues begin their names with
"<tt>soc.</tt>", and all of those groups that concern cultural discussions
start with "<tt>soc.culture.</tt>", so that that group on Brazillian
culture is <tt>soc.culture.brazil</tt>, Haitian culture is
<tt>soc.culture.haiti</tt>, and so on. (Notice the use of periods to
seperate the components of each name.) With some groups, the content is
moderated (e.g. <tt>soc.feminism</tt>), but most groups have no
restrictions at all (e.g. <tt>alt.feminism</tt>). There are thousands upon
thousands of newsgroups to choose from, containing postings from around the
world. Some web browsers (including Netscape) have newsreading capabilities
built in.

<ul>
<li><b><a href="http://scwww.ucs.indiana.edu/NetRsc/usenet.html">Usenet
Newsgroups: Resources</a>
<li><a href="http://gort.ucsd.edu/jj/news/eeg_69.html">EFF's (Extended)
Guide to the Internet: Usenet</a>
<li><a href="http://www.clari.net/brad/emily.html">Emily Postnews</a></b>
</ul>

<P>On LOL you have two ways to access Usenet newsgroups. Some groups are
available within LOL's forum area, for the most efficient possible access,
which you can use just as you would any other LOL forum. To access the rest
of Usenet, you can select a newsreader application from our <!--HREF
HERE-->Internet Page and install it on your computer. (We suggest <!--HERE
TOO-->Free Agent for Windows users.) Each of these applications comes with
its own instructions.

<a name="f"> </a>
<P><b>FTP</b> is a tool for transferring files. (It's short for <i>File
Transfer Protocal</i>.) You can download files on the World Wide Web (by
clicking on them), but FTP has the advantage of letting you send files to
another machine. When using FTP to connect to another machine, you need to
enter in a name and password -- don't worry, most FTP machines will let you
in if you enter "anonymous" for your name and your e-mail address for your
password. After that, FTP operates much like MS-DOS, if you've ever used
it: You type in short commands to navigate through directories and get or
put files. FTP is built in to most web browsers (though not all browsers
can send files -- you'll need a dedicated FTP program for that).

<ul>
<li><b><a
href="http://www.cis.ohio-state.edu/hypertext/faq/usenet/ftp-list/faq/faq.ht
ml">Anonymous FTP FAQ</a></b>
</ul>

<P>For Windows users LOL also provides an excellent FTP tool, called
CuteFTP, via the LOL <!--HREF HERE-->Internet Page. MAC Users can get a
comparable tool
from the LOL/ShareWorld Mac file library. Please consult the
instructions within LOL and your FTP programm's help system for more
information.

<a name="m"> </a>
<P><b>Mailing lists</b> are a special application of e-mail: You send an
e-mail message to a "listserver" (a specially configured machine) asking to
receive a particular mailing list. Then, whenever e-mail is posted to the
mailing list, the listserver will send copies to everyone on the list.
Typical mailing lists include newsletters and small discussion groups. For
example, to join ACTIV-L, a "discussion of peace, empowerment, justice and
environmental issues," send an e-mail message to <A
HREF="mailto:listserv@mizzou1.missouri.edu">listserv@mizzou1.missouri.edu</A
> containing the following text:

<blockquote>
<TT>subscribe ACTIV-L</TT>
</blockquote>

Be forewarned, however, that subscribing to too many mailing lists will
fill up your e-mail box with a large volume of mail. You can unsubscribe
from the above list by sending "<TT>signoff ACTIV-L</TT>" to the same
address. Other lists may require different commands for subscribing and
unsubscribing.

<ul>
<li>More info on <b><a
href="http://www.nova.edu/Inter-Links/listserv.html">E-mail Discussion
Groups</a>
<li><a href="http://catalog.com/vivian/interest-group-search.html">The List
of Lists</a>
<li><a href="http://www.tile.net/tile/listserv/ecology.html">Ecology
lists</b> (from tile.net)</a>
</ul>

<a name="t"> </a>
<P><b>Telnet</b> lets you "log in" to another machine on the Internet. This
is most commonly used to access "shell accounts" on UNIX machines (which
give you your own little space on a large, powerful computer), but is also
used for a variety of other applications, such as library catalog systems,
or BBS access via the Internet. LOL itself can be accessed using telnet,
including the telnet capability of our WG software for Windows.

<a name="g"> </a>
<P><b>Gopher</b> is a system that organizes information into a series of
menus. You can navigate between different machines and directories, and
retrieve files files simply by selecting from the menu choices. Think of it
as a more "user-friendly" front-end for FTP and Telnet that also integrates
information from many different sources. The World Wide Web has surpassed
Gopher in many of these functions, but there are still many valuable
resources accessible through Gopher.

<ul>
<li><b><a href="gopher://mudhoney.micro.umn.edu:70/00/Gopher.FAQ">Gopher
FAQ</a></b>
</ul>

<a name="i"> </a>
<P><b>IRC</b> (<i>Internet Relay Chat</i>) is kind of like a "live" Usenet:
The discussion groups are called "channels," and communication happens in
real time. Once you join a channel, you can type messages that appear
immediately on the screens of everyone else connected to the same channel.
There are a variety of special commands you can learn to enhance the
experience.

<ul>
<li><b><A HREF="http://www.kei.com/irc.html">IRC FAQ</A> (Frequently Asked
Questions)
<li><a
href="http://mistral.enst.fr/~pioch/IRC/IRCprimer/IRCprimer/IRCprimer.html">
A short IRC primer</a></b>
</ul>

<P>LOL provides an IRC tool, again on the <!--HREF HERE-->Internet Page. Please
consult the instructions there and in the tool's help system for further
guidance.

<center><table border><P>Go back to the <a href="guide.htm">Left On Line
Guide to the Internet</a></table></center>

</BODY></HTML>



