<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Chomsky Comment About Gingrich et. al.</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message from Noam Chomsky written for the AskZ&amp;C Forum,
responding to comments from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>
On Gingrich et. al. </H1>
<P>On Gingrich, Gramm, etc., I think you are right in saying we shouldn't
underestimate them, but what they (particularly Gingrich) say is so flaky it's
hard not to laugh. It certainly doesn't merit response. But what they are doing
makes perfect sense. Take, say, what happened when school lunches were under
discussion, and the Democrats made the tepid harassing gesture to keep the
roughly $6 billion in funding for hungry children by delaying -- DELAYING -- the
deployment of Lockheed F-22's (which we desperately need to counter the threat
of the F-16's that Lockheed is upgrading at taxpayer expense and &quot;selling&quot;
to third world dictatorships with taxpayer-guaranteed loans so they can
constitute a threat that requires us...). It was shot down very fast. Not for
nothing is Gingrich called &quot;the congressman from Lockheed.&quot; And others
also understand what happens to the high tech economy if this nonsense is
tolerated. So that's not pure flakishness, though his ravings are.</P>
<P>On protectionism, etc., I'm afraid I didn't follow. I don't see the
connection to Fish on free speech (which I didn't like, but for other reasons).
No one, not even the nuttiest &quot;libertarian,&quot; is so deluded as to think
that speech is not an act. Like most of the work in the postmodern cults, Fish
is contriving a straw man, then giving (in my view, terrible) arguments against
it. I also don't think much of his work on legal theory. But I don't follow what
that has to do with what we were discussing.</P>
<P>I also don't know what you mean by the measure of &quot;really free trade.&quot;
We know what that is well enough, abstractly, and no one advocates it for
themselves except for temporary advantage (though it's commonly rammed down the
throats of others). You seem to be interpreting my observations to this effect
as advocacy of free trade. They are not; that's an entirely separate issue.</P>
<P>I also disagree with you about restrictions on speech. Who does the
restricting? How do they get that power? If you want to restrict speech that
harms people, then let's be serious about it: for starters, bar all the
gibberish about free markets, which is used to smash people into the ground,
vastly more harmful than anything the Klan might do -- that is, shut down all
the institutions. I think you're pursuing entirely the wrong path in this
respect, irrespective of Scientific American.</P>
<P>I'm afraid I also didn't follow what you said about the sciences. As for
automatic parsers, I don't see that they have much to do with the sciences;
unless intended as a research tool, it's a form of engineering, and not a very
sophisticated form. The rest is amusing, however.</P>
<P>About the &quot;good old American contempt for theory,&quot; I suppose I
share it. To be precise, I am all in favor of &quot;theory&quot; when it is
real, and all opposed to it when it is posturing -- and there's plenty of that,
in my opinion. I don't know anything much that merits the term outside of parts
of the sciences. Most topics are just too hard, so we do basically descriptive
work (if we are intellectuals, pretending that it is &quot;theory&quot; --
that's part of the scam). If someone has some theories that have some
credibility and some conclusions, beyond the surface, in areas of human concern,
I'd like to hear them. So far, I've missed them. As for &quot;evading
philosophy,&quot; I spend a lot of my time and effort in the field called &quot;philosophy&quot;
(teaching, writing, lecturing, etc.), but don't know what it means to &quot;evade
philosophy,&quot; or not to, so honestly can't comment. I don't see what
philosophy or theory have to do with the quite serious question you raise about
public subsidies for computing initiatives. We probably disagree about this (so
I gather from your few remarks), but it's a serious question, and I don't know
of any theories or philosophy that bears on it.</P>
<P>Rawls's work is interesting, intellectually, but so remote from any
application to any actual questions that concern us that I don't see the
relevance here. The &quot;difference principle,&quot; plausible or not, isn't &quot;a
theory&quot; and doesn't require one. There are perfectly plain reasons why
those in a position to reject that operative principle do so, and why others who
seek greater justice strive for something like that. They did that before the
principle was enunciated, and do it in the same way afterwards. That's not to
say that his work is uninteresting; it's quite interesting, but in a completely
different intellectual universe.</P>
<P>It's true that FDR, JFK, etc., had corporate support, but that doesn't bear
on whether Clinton's was unusual. No one has studied the matter in depth, so
we're expressing opinions not based on extensive research (or even clear
criteria), but I think that he does have unusual corporate support, and I think
it's clear why. You're quite right about Clinton's policies -- which is one
reason why he has unusual corporate support, as the &quot;Wall St. J.&quot;
pointed out early on.</P>
<P>I also don't know what you mean by saying that the Republicans have
historically been the party of change. The parties have stood for all sorts of
things over the years, sometimes even interchanging positions overnight. Thus in
the 1984 elections, the Democrats were the party of fiscal conservatism and the
Republicans the party of borrow-and-spend abandon and forget tomorrow. The
Reaganites were also the party of extreme protectionism and state power. Right
now, the Gingrich wing of the party (there are some interesting splits within
big money circles) represents subsidies to high tech industry, fringe elements
of the economy (hedge funds, etc.), and popular forces mobilized around
religious fundamentalism, jingoist fanaticism, fear and hatred, and other such
(not unfamiliar) elements. They frighten the CEOs, in many ways -- again, not
something unprecedented -- enough so that even &quot;Fortune&quot; has been
concerned.</P>
<P>I didn't quite follow the rest, I'm afraid.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
