<p>&#160;</p>
<h2>What Is ShareWorld?</h2>
<p><img src="images/yellhat.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32> <a href="SWindex.htm">ShareWorld</a> is an encompassing community of online systems, one of which is LOL.</p>
<p>ShareWorld creates member-only systems for diverse progressive organizations such as The 
Wilderness Society (WOL), The Nation Magazine (NOL), Greenpeace (GOL), and us (LOL), 
and that maintains and operates the technology and handles support for all these systems. 
ShareWorld also provides diverse additional content beyond that offered by each sponsoring 
organization and provides linkage between these systems for sharing of their diverse offerings 
internally. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<h2>LOL's Contents</h2>
<p><img src="images/redhat.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32> Left on Line is a Web Site system that offers some unusual technical, social, and 
informational features such as: </p>
<blockquote>
<dl>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> an online school</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> a rich and extensive system of moderated forums</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> diverse polls about policy and social issues</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> user guidance re books, web sites, etc.</dt>
<dt>&#160;</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> paging other users online</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> a book club with low prices, reviews, and discussion groups</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> a user edited and written weekly magazine</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> a gallery of regularly updated user poetry</dt>
<dt>&#160;</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> audio for shows online and for &quot;phoning&quot;</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> advanced teleconferencing features</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> job placement and search facilities</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> free home page creation, maintainence, and editing for users</dt>
<dt>&#160;</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> Z Magazine back issues online, with author, issue, and topic lookup</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> research facilities with full text boolean searches of all files online</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> robust games like chess, backgammon, and others</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> safe and educational children's facilities and internet guidance</dt>
<dt>&#160;</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> an online store with socially responsible vendors</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> activism on line with associated faxing, emailing, and forums</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> file libraries with articles, shareware, etc. </dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> an acclaimed international online weekly magazine, <font color="#000000">Marble</font></dt>
<dt>&#160;</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> advanced plug-in modules for Windows users</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> extensive, easy to use web and internet guidance, regularly updated</dt>
<dt><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> non-commercial, politically serious, and informed content from a host of 
sponsors of diverse systems within the broader ShareWorld community</dt>
</dl>
</blockquote>
<p><img src="images/redhat.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32> To get a feeling for LOL's offerings consider what we call the Top Menu frame, to the upper 
left, and the Table of Contents frame, to the lower left. When you click in the top frame, new 
options appear in the lower one. </p>
<blockquote>
<p><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> If you are a member of LOL, then from the two navigation frames you get one 
click access to all system offerings. </p>
<p><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> If you are a non-member visitor to LOL, in many instances of clicking on an 
option in the Table of Contents Frame to the lower left you will get a notice that you 
can't access the offering without being an LOL member and asking if you would like 
to join. </p>
<p><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> Another option, which can be more convenient at times, is to use the pull down 
menus located at the top of many pages. These too provide access to many (though 
not all) features of the system. There are three pull down menus, the first gives 
functionality inside your browser and is relevant to everyone. The second gives 
access to Windows plug-in modules, only relevant, therefore, to Windows users. 
And the third gives access to our online tutorial, again for everyone.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><img src="images/redhat.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32> If you want to get a more detailed description of Left On Line and its offerings before you 
make the decision whether or not to join, the easiest way is to examine the many <strong>How To</strong> and 
other available menu options. </p>
<blockquote>
<p><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> Just click <strong>How To</strong> in the top left frame, and then click each item in turn in the 
lower left Table of Contents frame to see in this window a descriptive account of 
each discussed function. </p>
<p><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> Other sources of information about LOL can be found at the <a href="SWindex.htm">ShareWorld</a> site and 
the <a href="index.htm">ZNet</a> site.</p>
<p><img src="images/redarr3.gif" align=baseline width=24 height=21> You can join LOL using the button located aat the bottom of this page, or by 
clicking the the <strong>Join LOL</strong> option in the menu frame to the upper left.</p>
</blockquote>
<p align=center>&#160;<a href="http://lol.shareworld.com/chbin/main/logon?uid=guest&amp;pw=guest&amp;link=/chbin/mod/newuser"><font size=5><strong>Join Left-On-Line Now</strong></font></a></p>
<p align=center>&#160;</p>
<h2>Fees</h2>
<p><img src="images/bluehat.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32> Left On Line is not free. To remain a member of LOL you pay $8 a month for unlimited 
access from your browser to the full LOL site. The ZNet site, in contrast, though developed and 
maintained by the same people, is free. What's the difference?</p>
<ul>
<li>The ZNet site, like many free sites, attempts to reach out to new audience and to provide 
resources to a wide array of people not yet ready to become more directly involved and 
supportive. It is a public front room to attract people to various institutions and projects, 
including LOL. It has limited offerings and requires modest maintainence. The assumption 
that users are passing through...</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>The LOL site, on the other hand, is for a closed community of folks who are more 
committed to sustained and supportive involvement. It requires far more equipment and 
maintainence on our part and offers far more content, community, and functionality to you. 
The assumption is that users believe in the site, in the offerings, in the project, and want to 
not only benefit from it, but also support it.</li>
</ul>
<p><img src="images/bluehat.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32> Well and good, you might say, but still: why charge for it? Maintaining sites, whether public 
or private, involves paying fees for linkages, to maintain equipment, and, in particular, to 
continually refine and update content. Where is the money to do all this to come from? Currently, 
throughout the internet there are only three available options. </p>
<ul>
<li>Depend on ad revenue. </li>
<li>Charge users a regular fee, or </li>
<li>Have some agency or institution foot the bill as a donation. </li>
</ul>
<p><img src="images/bluehat.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32> We couldn't get sufficient ads for LOL even if we wanted them, but, more important, relying 
on ads would subvert our anti-commerical aims. We are not interested in selling users to 
corporate marketeers, which is precisely the business any ad driven site or periodical is in. We 
also lack a benefactor, however. So we need user support. The long and short of it, then, is this: </p>
<ul>
<li>We cannot moderate and enliven forums, provide ever-changing and enlarging online 
content, develop ever-diversifying modules and functionality, maintain reliable, robust 
equipment, attract and maintain writers and other content providers, etc., without charging a 
fee. </li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>We therefore hope you agree with us that getting self-sustaining and even surplus generating 
progressive and left telecommunications projects and sites into operation should be a 
priority for socially conscious folks, and we hope you will join us in the effort.</li>
</ul>
<p align=center><a href="http://lol.shareworld.com/chbin/main/logon?uid=guest&amp;pw=guest&amp;link=/chbin/mod/newuser"><font size=5><strong>Join Left-On-Line Now</strong></font></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>&#160;</p>
</body>

