<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>High School in Society</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
 
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Schools Forum, by a recent student
continuing and enlarging a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1> A young person argues against attending High School at all </H1>
<P>Now that I see there are some young people in this forum, I think it is a
perfect time for me to introduce an idea that is gaining lots of popularity
among young people. The idea is dropping out of high school -- not out of
laziness or convenience or anything like that, but as a method of self
preservation and liberation. </P>
<P>Some very bright young people are doing this for other than the traditional
reasons (need to get a job, move out of parents house, etc.) Now it is being
done to avoid indoctrination and service to the state, capital, patriarchy,
white supremacy, judeo-christian doctrine, and most of all -- adultocracy (my
word, not theirs).</P>
<P>There are already several books on the subject, mostly done by self-
publishers and the like (of course, they are far more relevant and insightful
than anything high schoolers will likely get their hands on in the classroom).
For instance, Grace Llewellyn's _The Teenage Liberation Handbook_ is among the
most popular advocates of dropping out and self-educating. The _Schoolstoppers
Textbook_ is another, this one produced by the Chicago Anarchist Youth
Federation. John Holt's _Freedom and Beyond_ is another. Several 'zines have
also appeared on the subject, including &quot;fhs&quot; (you figure it out), &quot;Unschooling
Ourselves&quot;, &quot;Drop Out&quot;, &quot;F.U.C.K.&quot;, &quot;Boy Does High
School Ever Suck&quot;, and &quot;Growing W/O Schooling&quot;. I haven't read
all of these books and 'zines myself (yet), but the jist is this:</P>
<P>A high school diploma is worthless; all it signifies is that you have been
through a sufficient amount of engineering (indoctrination, invalidation,
deprivation, coercion and abuse) at the hands of the white, male, capitalist,
authoritarian adult society. So get out!</P>
<P>What do schools have to offer young people? That is what I can't figure out.
Besides being places where kids learn John Taylor Gatto's six lessons -- (1) &quot;stay
in the class where you belong&quot;; (2) &quot;turn on and off like a light
switch&quot;; (3) &quot;...surrender your will to a predestined chain of command&quot;;
(4) &quot;only *I* determine what curriculum you will study&quot;; (5) &quot;Good
people wait for a teacher to tell them what to do&quot;; and (6) &quot;[You] are
being watched&quot; -- I really don't think much is taught at schools that could
not be learned better elsewhere. </P>
<P>And I'm not just talking about homeschooling. I'm talking about young people
teaching themselves and each other. Certain things do need to be taught by
adults. But I'd be willing to bet young people would be far more responsive to
their peers in a less structured, nonhierarchical environment. </P>
<P>As I get more information on this dropping out (up) thing, I'll be sure to
pass it on.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
