<html>

<head>
<title>LOLU: About</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#EEFFFA" link="#CC0000" vlink="#000055"
alink="#FF3300" stylesrc="frwhatsnew.htm">

<h1><img src="../gifs/about.gif" alt="About " align="absbottom"
width="92" height="22"> <a href="index.htm"><img
src="../gifs/hlolu.gif" alt="LOLU" align="bottom" border="0"
hspace="8" width="96" height="28"></a> </h1>

<hr>

<blockquote>
    <h3>Purpose</h3>
    <p>Left On Line University aims to provide high quality
    courses across a range of disciplines and topics,
    inexpensively, and via telecommunications. In this way it
    provides access to quality faculty and classmates to people
    from all over the world. LOLU simultaneously raises
    consciousness and creates new ties among people who share the
    LOLU experience. </p>
    <h3>Structure</h3>
    <p>Each course runs for 10-15 weeks, the duration of each
    LOLU semester. Lecture courses involve weekly lectures posted
    by the faculty, and week-long discussions of the contents and
    derivative issues. Reading courses function similarly, but
    with reading assignments rather than lectures as the basis of
    discussion. </p>
    <p>Decisions as to what course shall be given rest ultimate
    with the LOLU staff. But the procedure for organizing and
    offering a course is to petition any LOL co-sponsor to
    sponsor the course, in which case, other than for redundancy,
    the course will appear in the LOLU catalog. </p>
    <h3>Finances</h3>
    <p>The current fees for course are $75 to take a course, and
    $30 to audit. There are special considerations given to those
    who truly cannot afford the going rates, though, since these
    fees are already very low, only the most extreme
    circumstances lead to further reductions. </p>
    <p>The revenues of LOLU are divided, 50% to the faculty and
    50% to the University Project. The faculty divide up their
    share of the income partially proportionately to the size of
    their classes, partially on a one course one share basis. </p>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
