<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>LBBS:About</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFA" link="#CC0000" vlink="#000055"
alink="#FF3300">

<h1><img src="../gifs/about.gif" alt="About " align="absbottom"
hspace="2" width="92" height="22"> <img
src="../images/frloli1.gif" width="105" height="23"></h1>

<hr>

<blockquote>
    <h2>What Is Left On Line</h2>
    <p>LOL is an online community. You join LOL to gain access to
    Left On Line's diverse facilities and offerings, plus
    offerings from a number of other &quot;connected&quot;
    systems that together compose the ShareWorld community of
    online systems.</p>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p>Click here to go to the <a
                href="http://www.lol.shareworld.com/leftonl/lolentry.htm"><font
                size="2" face="Arial"><strong>LOL Visitors Site</strong></font></a>
                to find out more about LOL and, if you wish, to
                join.</p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
    <p>Once you do join the LOL community, you access LOL with
    your web browser, preferably Netscape or Microsoft Explorer.
    The one constraint is that you need a browser that handles
    frames, for best effect.</p>
    <p>LOL is now nearing completion and offers or will soon
    offer:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><p align="left">E-Mail and diverse forums including
            participants like Noam Chomsky and Michael Albert of
            Z Magazine, with a far better interface than typical
            web systems </p>
        </li>
        <li><p align="left">Huge stores of information and
            resources, search engines, a book club (for purchases
            and discussion groups, etc.), a childrens center, an
            online school, etc. </p>
        </li>
        <li><p align="left">A congenial hassle-free environment
            with a community of mutually supportive users plus
            access to the entire encompassing <a
            href="http://www.shareworld.com"><font size="2"
            face="Arial"><strong>ShareWorld</strong></font></a>
            community and its offerings </p>
        </li>
        <li><p align="left">A user edited and written weekly
            magazine, and an online international weekly magazine
            and a poetry center for users' publications </p>
        </li>
        <li><p align="left">Diverse program functionality ranging
            from online games like chess, to activism modules,
            faxing capability, calendars, polling,
            teleconferencing, etc., audio and video functions,
            point and click ease of use, an online school with
            extensive course offerings, children's offerings, and
            so on. </p>
        </li>
        <li><p align="left">Extensive Internet and Web guidance </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p align="left">LOL is like having your own private America
    On Line, shared with a community of comparably committed and
    politically aware users, all linked to many other progressive
    socially responsible systems, and to the whole internet. It
    is a telecommunications home where one can learn, interact,
    react, and create within a mutually supportive community. And
    it is also a base for forays outward with the best editorial
    advice and guidance around.</p>
    <p>These functions are all accessible within your main
    browser windows, or via plug in modules that download
    automatically and install in your computer, like this Windows
    Chess module.</p>
    <p><img src="../images/frabou2.gif" width="696" height="558"></p>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <h2>Purpose</h2>
    <p>The Left Bulletin Board System, or Left On Line (or LOL)
    aims to become a continuous town meeting of large sectors of
    the progressive community providing useful information,
    facilitating exchange of ideas, hosting conferences,
    developing new political program and unity, facilitating on
    line activism, and acclimating progressive people to new
    technologies. </p>
    <h2 align="center">[<a
    href="http://www.lol.shareworld.com/leftonl/lolentry.htm">Visit
    and, if you like it, Join LOL</a>]</h2>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <h2>Organizational Structure</h2>
    <p>LOL is a system within the <a
    href="http://www.shareworld.com"><font size="3"><strong>ShareWorld</strong></font></a><font
    size="2"><strong> </strong></font>community of online
    systems. Shareworld creates custom designed systems for
    diverse progressive organizations such as The Wilderness
    Society (WOL), The Nation Magazine (NOL), and many others.
    ShareWorld maintains and operates the technology, handles tech
    support, etc. for all these systems, including Left On Line.
    The online content of LOL itself, however, is directly
    maintained by its sysop, <a href="../zmag/fralbert.htm">Michael
    Albert</a> of Z Magazine.</p>
    <p>Each of the systems in ShareWorld has its own interface,
    design, and special features. All of them share many of their
    content offerings among the whole community of ShareWorld
    systems, however.</p>
    <p>We would give you some screen shots to look at here, but
    it is easier for you just to go to our visitors site and look
    for yourself. If you are not a member you have only limited
    access from the visitors site, though you can join directly
    via your computer link up.</p>
    <h2 align="center">[<a
    href="http://www.lol.shareworld.com/leftonl/lolentry.htm">Visit
    and, if you like it, Join LOL</a>]</h2>
    <p>&nbsp; </p>
    <h2>Finances</h2>
    <p>Revenues to LOL derive from fees paid by users (find out
    how to <a href="frsubscrib.htm">subscribe to LOL</a>): </p>
    <ul>
        <li>there are monthly fees for all typical functions </li>
        <li>there are special fees (only) for taking an online
            course or buying a book or other product</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Incoming fees pay for maintaining the system and
    continually upgrading it, for getting content for the system,
    for maintaining internet connectivity sufficient to usage
    levels, for technical support, etc. Also, a considerable
    portion of LOL fees go to funding left projects and
    institutions of diverse types and range. </p>
    <h2 align="center">[<a
    href="http://www.lol.shareworld.com/leftonl/lolentry.htm">Visit
    and, if you like it, Join LOL</a>]</h2>
</blockquote>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
</body>
</html>
