<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Z Magazine: About Z -- Frame</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#EEFFFA" link="#CC0000" vlink="#000055"
alink="#FF3300">

<blockquote>
    <h2><img src="../gifs/about.gif" alt="About " align="top"
    hspace="4" width="92" height="22"> <a href="index.htm"><img
    src="../gifs/mdzmag.gif" alt="Z Magazine" align="top"
    border="0" width="216" height="75"></a> </h2>
</blockquote>

<p>&nbsp; </p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h2>Purposes and Policies</h2>
        <blockquote>
            <p><em><strong>Z</strong></em> is an independent
            political magazine of critical thinking on political, cultural, social, and
            economic life in the United States. It sees the
            racial, sexual, political, and class dimensions of
            personal life as fundamental to understanding and improving
            contemporary circumstances and it aims to assist
            activist efforts to attain a better future. </p>
            <p>To these ends, <em><strong>Z</strong></em>
            attempts to operate in a democratic fashion, both internally and also with
            respect to its contributing writers and artists and
            the broader national progressive community. </p>
            <p><em><strong>Z</strong></em> accepts no paid
            advertising. Our product is the magazine, not readers
            in turn sold to advertisers.</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h2>Editorial Policies and Author Relations</h2>
        <blockquote>
            <p><em><strong>Z</strong></em>'s monthly contents are
            an amalgam of pieces pre-contracted with regular writers and artists
            as well as freelance submissions chosen at the time
            of publication. </p>
            <p>The choice of articles is guided by our purposes
            and the desire to have original material, rather than merely
            duplicating coverage available in other venues. </p>
            <p><em><strong>Z</strong></em>'s author relations are
            rooted in the idea that writers know what they want
            to say and should not have to give up control of the
            way they want to say it. Our regular writers have almost
            unlimited control over their own space in the magazine,
            and we also avoid at all costs editing the ideas of freelance pieces,
            though we often do have to edit freelance submissions
            for style and length. </p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h2>Finances</h2>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <p><em><strong>Z</strong></em><strong> </strong>accepts
            no paid advertising. <strong><i>Z</i></strong>'s
            income derives from: </p>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
    <hr>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <pre>
                                      Projected 1997:

subscriptions (new and renewal) . . . . . . $340,000
newsstand sales  . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  50,000
``ancillary funds'': small donations  . . . . 30,000
     included with renewals,
     sales of tapes and videos, etc.
list rental fees . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  10,000
large donor revenues  . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  0
advertising revenues . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 0
<strong>Total:</strong> . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  430,000
</pre>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
    <hr>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <p>The costs <i>Z</i> incurs are a bit more varied. The
            big items are: </p>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
    <hr>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <pre>
                                      Projected 1997:

printing and postage . . . . . . . . . . .  $150,000
payroll and taxes . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 85,000
    for our staff of three 
writers and artists payments . . . . . . . .  65,000
promotional solicitation mailings to  . . . . 60,000
    attract new subscribers
equipment, legal fees, . . . . . . . . . . .  50,000
    accountant fees, materials,
    renewal mailings, general postage,
    phone, etc., etc.
rent  . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 20,000
<strong>Total:</strong>  . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 430,000
</pre>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
    <hr>
    <p>The exact match is called budgeting. In practice, of
    course, many of the numbers will vary from this prediction.
    One disconcerting variation will arise from ongoing large
    increases in postal rates and paper costs. In any event, when
    costs rise, or some revenue declines, the resulting gap must
    be eliminated by increases in another revenue item--generally
    either donations or ancillary sales. We have no room to push
    costs further down. </p>
    <p>In light of our financial needs, we are always happy to
    accept donations. We are a tax exempt 501C3 institution and
    you can reach us at: </p>
    <blockquote>
        <p><strong>Z Magazine</strong> <br>
        18 Millfield Street <br>
        Woods Hole MA 02543. </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>Our phone number is (508) 548-9063. Or you can send e-mail
    to <a href="mailto:sysop@lol.shareworld.com">sysop@lol.shareworld.com</a></p>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
