<html>

<head>
<title>Hahnel</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body stylesrc="../zmag/frabout.htm">

<p><a><img src="../gifs/smlolu.gif" alt="LOLU | " align="middle"
hspace="4" width="144" height="71"> </a></p>

<h1>Course Outline--Introduction to Political Economy</h1>

<blockquote>
    <p>Instructor: Robin Hahnel, Professor, Department of
    Economics The American University, Washington DC 20016 Phone:
    202-885-2712; Fax 202-885-3790</p>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<p>Week 1: What are economies? How is the economic sphere of
social life related to other spheres of social life? How should
we evaluate the performance of economies?</p>

<p>Readings (readings are all optional, the course can be
followed solely paying attention to on line lectures):</p>

<p>Albert, Cagan, Chomsky, Hahnel, King, Sargent, Sklar,
Liberating Theory (Boston: South End Press, 1986), Chapters 1-6;
pp. 5-93.</p>

<p>Hahnel and Albert, Quiet Revolution in Welfare Economics,
(Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1990), [QR] Chapters 5
and 6*.</p>

<p>Albert and Hahnel, The Political Economy of Participatory
Economics (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1991), [PEPE]
pp. 7-11.</p>

<hr>

<p>Weeks 2,3,4: Different ways of deciding What to produce? How
to produce it? How to use it? Classes, Oppression, and
Exploitation.</p>

<p>Readings:</p>

<p>&quot;The Professional Managerial Class&quot; by Barbara and
John Ehrenreich, &quot;Intellectuals and the Class Structure of
Capitalist Society&quot; by Erik Olin Wright, and &quot;A Ticket
to Ride: More Locations on the Class Map&quot; by Albert and
Hahnel all in Pat Walker, ed., Between Labor and Capital (Boston:
South End Press, 1979),</p>

<p>John Roemer, Free to Lose (Cambridge: Harvard University
Press, 1988), Chapters 2,5,6* and 7*.</p>

<hr>

<p>Weeks 5,6: Markets: What they Do and How to Evaluate Them.
Invisible Hand or Invisible Foot? Equity and Social Effects.</p>

<p>Readings:</p>

<p>Bradley Schiller, The Economy Today, 6th ed. (NY: McGraw Hill,
1994), [Schiller] Chapter 3.</p>

<p>Robert Heilbroner, The Worldly Philosophers, 6th ed. (NY:
Simon and Schuster), Chapter III.</p>

<p>[QR] pp. 61-64; 226-240.</p>

<p>Samuel Bowles, &quot;What Markets Can and Cannot Do,&quot; in
Challenge Magazine, July-August 1991.</p>

<p>Albert and Hahnel, &quot;Why Participatory Planning,&quot; in
Z Papers, April-June 1994, pp. 25-32.</p>

<hr>

<p>Weeks 7,8,9: The Collapse of Communism and the debate between
Capitalism, Market &quot;Socialism,&quot; and Participatory
Economics.</p>

<p>Readings:</p>

<p>David Kotz, &quot;The Collapse of State Socialism in the USSR:
Lessons for a Future Socialism.&quot;</p>

<p>Hahnel and Albert, &quot;Revolutions in the East,&quot; in Z
Magazine, April 1990.</p>

<p>Milton Friedman, Capitalism and Freedom, (Chicago: University
of Chicago Press, 1982), Introduction and Chapters I,II, and X.</p>

<p>[PEPE] Chapters 1,2,3,4,5*</p>

<p>Albert and Hahnel, &quot;Why Participatory Planning,&quot; in
Z Papers, July-August 1994, pp. 32-47.</p>

<p>Articles by Thomas Weisskopf, David Schweickart, Albert and
Hahnel, and Pat Devine in the special issue on the &quot;Future
of Socialism&quot; of the Review of Radical Political Economics,
Fall-Winter 1992, Vol. 24 Nos. 3&amp;4. (URPE C/O Department of
Economics, University of California at Riverside, Riverside CA
92521)</p>

<p>&quot;Economic Roundtable on Looking Forward&quot; in Z
Magazine, July-August 1991.</p>

<p>John Roemer, &quot;A Future for Socialism&quot; in the
Newsletter of the Committee on the Political Economy of the Good
Society, Winter 1993.</p>

<p>Robin Hahnel, &quot;Book Review of A Future for
Socialism,&quot; in Z Magazine, October 1994.</p>

<hr>

<p>Weeks 10,11,12: The Macroeconomics of Capitalism: Causes of
unemployment and inflation; The logic of fiscal and monetary
policy; Politics of the budget; Schools of thought. Comparisons
between US, Japanese, French, British, and Swedish Capitalisms.</p>

<p>Readings:</p>

<p>[Schiller] Chapters 5,6,8,9,10; 11,12,13,14,15</p>

<hr>

<p>Weeks 13,14: International Economics: What Causes Trade? How
to Interpret Balance of Payments. Mutual Benefit or Imperialism?</p>

<p>Readings:</p>

<p>Peter Lindert, International Economics, 9th ed., (Boston:
Richard Irwin, 1991), Chapters 2,3,4*</p>

<p>[Schiller] Chapters 35 and 17</p>

<p>Robin Hahnel, &quot;Cooperacion International, Si! NAFTA,
No!&quot; in Z Magazine, April 1993.</p>

<hr>

<p>Week 15: Markets and Environmental Destruction: The Political
Economy of Environmental Regulation.</p>

<p>Readings:</p>

<p>[Schiller] Chapter 28 Eban Goodstein, Economics and the
Environment, (NJ: Prentice Hall, 1995) Chapters 1,2, and 3.</p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
