<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.ns.doe.ca//aeb/ssd/Acid/acidFAQ.html">The
Acid Rain FAQ comes courtesy of Environment Canada's </a><a href="http://www.ns.doe.ca//aeb/ssd/primer.html">A
Primer on Environmental Citizenship</a><a href="http://www.ns.doe.ca//aeb/ssd/Acid/acidFAQ.html">.
</a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://mxe115.rh.psu.edu/index.htm">Action Center Homepage
<font SIZE=-1>(Added: 12/7/95)</font> </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://mxe115.rh.psu.edu/index.htm">Billed
as an &quot;activists' center for training in organizing and networking,&quot;
it is a collection of very good material (plus some links) to aid the progressive
activist. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://hoshi.cic.sfu.ca/adbusters/">Adbusters' Culture
Jammers Headquarters</a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://hoshi.cic.sfu.ca/adbusters/">A
great site done by Adbusters, a group that fights fire with fire. As they
say, &quot;we will take on the archetypal mind polluters -- Marlboro, Budweiser,
Benetton, Coke, McDonald's, Calvin Klein -- and beat them at their own
game.&quot; See their ads that fly in the face of billion dollar images.
</a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.aflcio.org">AFL-CIO</a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.aflcio.org">The AFL-CIO web
site hosts information about the AFL-CIO and resources valuable to anyone
interested in labor. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/race/aanews">African
American News Service </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/race/aanews">The
African American News Service is sponsored by the Institute for Global
Communications and serves as an alternative source for news relating to
the African American community. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.anc.org.za/">African National Congress Home
Page </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.anc.org.za/">The African National
Congress has a stunning web site complete with links to other South African
resources. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.aclu.org">American Civil Liberties Union
</a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.aclu.org">The American Civil
Liberties Union has taken the Web by storm with its Freedom Network. There's
too much to describe here. Just go there and spend a day or two. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.apn.com/">American Political Network <font SIZE=-1>(Added:
1/4/96)</font> </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.apn.com/">Do you want to get
&quot;virtually&quot; inside the Beltway? Then the APN is the place to
be. Such offerings as The Hotline, American Healthline, and Greenwire,
each offered daily, will ensure that you never miss a beat. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.io.org/amnesty/">Amnesty International Online
<font SIZE=-1>(Added: 7/6/95)</font> </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.io.org/amnesty/">Amnesty International
is now on the web. Among the site's highlights: AI's 1994 country reports,
details on current Amnesty projects, and links to other human rights resources
on the Internet. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/index.html">Animal Rights
Resource Site <font SIZE=-1>(Added: 7/6/95)</font> </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/index.html">The
Animal Rights Resource Site (which now includes the former Animal Defense
Network) maintains a wealth of information about animal rights and hosts
the web pages of many </a><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/homepages.html">other
animal rights groups</a><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/index.html">.
The </a><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/gallery/gallery.html">picture
gallery</a><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/index.html"> displays particularly
alarming photographic evidence of cruelty to animals. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com">The Atlantic</a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com">Since 1857,
the Atlantic has provided intellectual coverage of politics, society, culture
and the arts. The magazine, which falls somewhere between the Nation and
Harpers, presents a Web site full of its writing, and now offers the </a><a href="http://www2.theAtlantic.com/atlantic/election/connection/">Election
Connection</a><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com">. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.enews.com:80/magazines/body/">Body Politic
<font SIZE=-1>(Added: 7/31/95)</font> </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.enews.com:80/magazines/body/">Body
Politic is a pro-choice magazine ironically based in Binghamton, New York
-- the birthplace of Operation Rescue. Its web site offers gopher access
to some articles as well as information on subscribing. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/">The Body Shop <font SIZE=-1>(Added:
7/6/95)</font> </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/">The business
of the Body Shop is the manufacture and retail of beauty products. At the
same time, the Body Shop is concerned with being a good citizen of the
world. The Body Shop's Web site currently focuses on the latter task, with
resources pertaining to </a><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/action.html">human
rights</a><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/"> and the </a><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/es.html">environment</a><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/">.
</a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://www.cais.com/agf/cwindex.htm">Catholic Worker
Home Page <font SIZE=-1>(Added: 1/11/96)</font> </a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.cais.com/agf/cwindex.htm">This
is an unofficial page done by an admirer of the Catholic Worker movement.
The movement, born during the Great Depression, aims to provide food, clothing,
shelter and welcome the needy in poor areas, both urban and rural. There
are 134 Catholic Worker Houses of Hospitality, each of which is listed
on the site. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

<dt><b><i><a href="http://latino.sscnet.ucla.edu/">Chicano/Latino Network
</a></i></b></dt>

<dd><b><i><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://latino.sscnet.ucla.edu/">The Chicano/Latino
Network (CLNet), is a &quot;general Latino focused Internet site serving
all segments of the community.&quot; It is based at UCLA and offers a wide
variety of information, ranging from resources for academic research on
Latino issues to job listings. </a></font></i></b></dd>

<dt>
<hr></dt>

