<html>

<head>
<title>Schor Lecture</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body stylesrc="../zmag/frabout.htm">

<p><a><img src="../gifs/smlolu.gif" alt="LOLU | " align="middle"
hspace="4" width="144" height="71"> </a><a href="../index.htm"> </a> <a
href="mailto:zsysop@zbbs.com"> </a></p>

<hr>

<h1>Consumerism: Lecture 3</h1>

<h2>More on &quot;Keeping up with the Joneses.&quot;</h2>

<address>
    Faculty: Juliet Schor
</address>

<hr>

<p>This week, I thought I would discuss the major work on
&quot;keeping up with the Joneses,&quot; or status competition to
have come out in the last two decades, namely Robert Frank's
CHOOSING THE RIGHT POND (New York: Oxford University Press,
1985). Frank is an interesting and eclectic economist from
Cornell University, who argues that the phenomenon of
status-seeking is is pervasive in our society, that economists
have largely ignored it, and that the attempts to gain status can
explain much of the way labor markets, consumer markets, and
other aspects of the economy operate. I don't endorse his
criticisms of the left particularly, but I think this book has a
lot to say. The title Choosing the Right Pond refers to the fact
that people can choose to be little fish in big ponds or big fish
in little ponds, and that their attitdues about status will
inform those choices. What follows is a summary of Frank's
arguments:</p>

<p>1. The importance of relative position and relative income.
Duesenberry (and others we talked about last week) argue that
what matters to people is not just their absolute level of
income, but their relative income. This conclusion is supported
by some classic evidence, cited in most discussions on relative
income. First, Frank notes that surveys of happiness show that
rising absolute levels of income are not associated with rising
absolute incomes. (I also discuss this evidence in chapter 5 of
my book, The Overworked American.) For example, in the United
States, there is no rise in happiness over the period 1946-1970,
a period when average incomes rose dramatically. (For those
sceptical of opinion measures, self-reported happiness scores are
correlated with &quot;objective&quot; measures of people's
well-being.) Second, Frank refers to the classic evidence of
Richard Easterlin, who found that happiness does rise with
income, at any given time. That is, within any country, at a
given time, higher income people are happier, and lower income
people less happy. This will hold true as their average income
rises as well. And he found that across countries, the
relationship does not hold. People in poor countries are as happy
(on average) as those in rich countries. (This evidence has
changed in recent years, perhaps because a more globalized world
has made those in poor countries more aware of where they stand
relative to rich country dwellers. Television, movies,
international travel and migration may have been responsible for
this change.) Another piece of evidence is that the amount of
money Americans report is necessary to live decently rises almost
in parallel fashion with average incomes. Our expectations and
&quot;needs&quot; are not determined so much by absolute levels,
as by social norms. These norms are the basis of social
comparisons. </p>

<p>2. Is status seeking a biological imperative? Frank starts
with a BIOLOGICAL model, in which he argues that evidence from
animal studies, as well as some human studies, indicate that the
quest for status is an innate characteristic of human beings. He
cites studies in which humans' heart rate and pulse are measured
in social situations. These find that people tend to have a
higher heart rate and faster pulse when they are in social
situations with people of a higher social status. He also looks
at monkey studies show dominant monkeys have higher levels of
serotonin. (So do officers of college fraternities and leaders of
athletic teams!) Third, he argues that humans display a herd
instinct, in which we follow each other in status contests. He
also provides anecdotal evidence about children's behavior,
arguing that by the time we reach adulthood we have been taught
to repress many of our natural desires for status (we are taught
that those feelings are shameful and anti-social.) In the
children's example, he performs an experiemnt on his children,
giving them different levels of organe juice each day. He finds
that they don't mind getting less juice when both of them receive
less. It's when there's a disparity in what he pours out to them
that the trouble starts. </p>

<p>Is status-seeking biological? My answer at this point is that
we don't really know. I am generally sceptical of biological
explanations for social phenomenon. I don't think we know much
about &quot;human nature&quot; at all. Among both animals and
humans the range of social interaction is so wide that it's hard
to draw a link to biology. The animal studies Frank cites are
hardly compelling, because it's almost always possible to find
animal studies showing opposite kinds of behavior. Where I do
agree with Frank is that the drive for social status seems to be
very pervasive in our own society. And I think that's what really
matters at this point.</p>

<p>3. Who are we in competition with? For most of us, it's not
Donald Trump, the Rockefellers, or the folks on Dynasty. It's
people in our own circles. Our neighbors, co-workers, relatives,
friends, etc. Most people choose their frames of comparison
realistically, focussing on people near us in the hierarchy. We
know the Rockefellers are out of reach. The buying patterns of
the people next door will have more of an impact on us. Objects
of comparison (or what are called reference groups) are also
multiple. That is, we won't just compare ourselves to ONE set of
people. If we interact with a number of types of people, we will
have overlapping and varied reference groups. For example,
employees tend to have strong reference group identification with
co-workers, but also with neighbors. (I will provide some survey
evidence on this in a later lecture.) The media MAY also be
important here. One argument is that popular
culture/media/advertising, by exposing us all to a common
lifestyle, can create a national reference group that large
numbers of people relate to. And if Hollywood and television show
lifestyles are above the level most people can afford (as they
are), exposure to media can generate dissatisfaction, desires to
emulate, and aspirations which are beyond people's capability to
achieve. (If this sounds like it is counter to what I argued last
week, I don't think it is. My argument is not that the media is
irrelevant, but that it operates within, or on top of, this
underlying context of social emulation/status competition.)</p>

<p>4. What do we compete about: the crucial role of visibility in
social competitions. As we begin to think about the dynamics of
status competition, it becomes clear that not all goods or
activities can serve equally well in status competitions. In
particular, those things we are competing over need to be
somewhat &quot;socially visible.&quot; Why? If they are not,
who's to know we have them, and how can the desire to emulate be
transmitted? To a certain extent, there is a credibility problem
here. If I am trying to gain social status, I can brag about
having particular things (like a fat bank account, or a safe
deposit box full of valuables), but I may not be telling the
truth. Why will others believe me? If the goods we compete about
are visible, there's no need to advertise what we have. It is
evident and obvious. Visibility also deals with another problem
associated with status. If you try too hard to get it, you can't.
Striving for status can backfire, as the nouveau riche often
painfully find out. Sorting out the credibility and legitimacy of
status claims is a key part of the game. For example, in
eighteenth century England, when an emerging bourgeoisie was
attempting to rise socially, the aristocrats and landed gentry
developed a social system based on &quot;patina&quot; to
de-legitimize the claims of these nouveau riche. What was patina?
It was the inevitable signs of age that goods achieve as they are
passed from generation to generation. Anthropologist Grant
McCracken in his book, CULTURE AND CONSUMPTION (Bloomington:
Indiana University Press, 1990, ch 2 on patina) argues that the
patina system was the dominant system of social organization
until sometime in the eighteenth century. At the height of the
patina system, pretenders would try and counterfeit status by
acquiring used goods, or by trying to make new ones look good.
(Hence the use of family crests, etc., which make it impossible
to use another family's possession to acquire status for
yourself.) It is easy to see how, in a society of fashion and
mass consumption, the patina system cannot survive. Status began
to be associated with novelty. Today, and since the 18th century,
only the rich still practice a status system based on patina. </p>

<p>But to return to social visibility. Patina was one system
based on socially visible goods and their characteristics. We may
have abandoned patina, but socially visible goods are still the
lynchpin of social competitions. What are they? Cars, houses,
furniture and clothes are the most obvious examples of modern
status symbols. If we think carefully about patterns of buying,
we can see how visibility plays a role. Take furniture. Where is
the fanciest furniture in the house? The most public (and
ironically least used room), the living room. Which will be the
least well-decorated? The bedrooms (most private). (Where will
people hang curtains last, or not at all? Bedrooms.) What about
clothes? The prestige of the &quot;brand&quot; people wear rises
as we move from undergarments to coats and overcoats? It is my
contention that in a whole range of products, the evidence will
show that the prices paid, and the status of brand names bought
will rise with the level of &quot;social visibility&quot; of the
product. </p>

<p>In a recent paper I have written with a former student, Angela
Chao, entitled &quot;Empirical Tests of Status Consumption:
Evidence from Women's Cosmetics&quot; we test just this idea. We
have gathered both quality and price data on four cosmetics
products: lipsticks, mascara, eyeshadow, and facial cleansers.
These four have significantly different levels of social
visibility. Lipsticks are taken out in public (at dinner tables,
in meetings, etc.) Eyeshadows and mascaras are semi-public, seen
more in women's &quot;powder rooms&quot; but sometimes in full
view. And facial cleansers are only used in the privacy of
women's own homes. We hypothesize two things. First, that the
relationship between price and quality will be weaker the more
socially visible the product. And second, that we will find more
&quot;high-end&quot; or high- priced buying among the visible
products. Both these hypotheses turned out to be strongly
supported by our evidence. With lipsticks, the most visible good,
there is NO relationship between price and quality. In fact, all
lipsticks (within type, ie., matte, shiny, etc.) are made of
identical ingredients and in blind &quot;taste-tests&quot;
consumers cannot tell the difference between cheap and expensive
lipsticks. In fact, in one extreme example, consumers could not
differentiate between Flame Glow (a low- status brand selling at
$18.83 an ounce) and Chanel (perhaps the most prestige name of
all, selling at $181,24 an ounce). When the lipsicks were in
generic containers, just as many women preferred Flame Glow as
chose Chanel. Why then are women paying $25 for a Chanel lipstick
when they can get an identical product for $2? Our answer: the
social status associated with Chanel, and the social embarassment
of pulling out the $2 brand. By contrast, women do demand
somewhat more quality in their choice of facial cleansers, where
it turns out that more expensive brands are ranked more highly in
terms of quality.</p>

<p>We also found strong differences in how women buy, based on
social visibility. There is much more &quot;high end&quot; buying
in lipsticks than facial cleansers, and an intermediate amount in
the eyeshadows and mascaras, exactly as we predicted. We also
found differences in the extent to which different types of women
seek status. Women with more education and more income do more
status buying. Women in cities and suburbs, and white women are
also more status-conscious. These are exactly the patterns we
expected.</p>

<p>We think that if we replicated this kind of study for other
products (clothes, houses, cars, furniture, etc.) we would find
similar patterns. Up to this point, however, we have not been
able to find the kinds of data we need to do so.</p>

<p>5. Status goods as &quot;signals&quot; and the need to keep
up. This point relates to the interesting comments made by Holly
Pence in response to last week's lecture. As she argued, there
are strong pressures for individuals to &quot;keep up&quot; in
the status game. If you are looking for a job, or trying to
succeed in one, bucking the standard marks of status can be
interpreted as a &quot;signal&quot; that you are failing. (i.e.,
clothes below the standard, a beat-up car in a management
environment, etc.) In interviews I have done with women who have
&quot;downshifted&quot; (ie., are dropping down or out of the rat
race), the expenses of maintaining a professional wardrobe
continually comes up. These women may not necessarily enjoy
shopping or spending their money on clothes, but they feel it is
necessary to appear to be successful and competent. Similarly,
for people whose jobs involve impressing clients, the appearance
of success is important (a nice office, a good car, expensive
clothes). If you look too shabby, your ability will be
questioned. Why? Because spending is a signal of income which is
taken to be indicative of ability. As long as the society
operates with a status system (as all do, in one way or another),
the pressures on individuals to conform are strong. And our
particular system is one which focusses on SOCIALLY VISIBLE
CONSUMER GOODS.</p>

<p>6. Prisoners' dilemmas and inadequate incentives for
non-visible goods. Once the competition is oriented to socially
visible goods, it becomes obvious that socially invisible goods
will be underproduced and underdemanded. Important examples are
public goods, occupational health and safety, savings, and
leisure, none of which focus as status symbols, and all of which
are in inadequate supply in our economy today. Why? Think of a
two person competition, between Smith and Jones. Let's say
they're competing about visible consumer goods and what matters
is their relative positions. In a 12 hour day, they could each
work 8 hours a day with 4 hours leisure, or 12 hours a day with
no leisure. If they both work 12, they will both have the same
income, (and hence be equally socially), but no leisure. This is
the worst outcome for both. Smith could work 8 hours a day, but
if Jones works 12, he or she will be behind socially (because
Smith's income will be lower). The converse is also true. The
best outcome for both would be an 8 hour day, with 4 hours of
leisure and an equal position for each. The prisoner's dilemma (a
solution to a standard game theory problem) is that by
cooperating they could get to the best outcome (the 8 hour day).
But because we have a non-cooperative, decentralized, market
system, they cannot cooperate. They will both be forced to work
as hard as they can in order to compete. The outcome will be the
12 hour day for both. They're both worse off, but without
cooperation neither trusts that the other will stay at 8. (and
neither will). [The name prisoner's dilemma comes from the famous
example of two prisoners who both confess, (the uncooperative
solution), and both go to jail, rather than both keep silent (the
cooperative solution) and go free. Each fears the other is
confessing, and so is driven to confess him or herself. This is
what happens in our example. Both Jones and Smith fear the other
will work longer hours, and thereby get ahead in the
competition.]</p>

<p>This example shows one reason why we don't have enough leisure
in our society, why people don't save enough, or why the pressure
to reduce taxes for public consumption goods is so strong. We are
so heavily oriented toward STATUS COMPETITION IN PRIVATE, VISIBLE
GOODS. There are lots of reasons to think this competition got
worse in the 1980s. And that various social restraints on such
competition are weakening. And once again, this is an example of
how advertising and the media can have an effect--through their
exacerbation of this competition. </p>

<p>7. Final point: The need for a centralized, cooperative
intervention. The prisoner's dilemma problem (the failure to
achieve a better, cooperative solution) shows why we need
government intervention in the market to steer us from too much
destructive status competition. As Robert Frank argues, this is
the rationale behind having uniforms in high schools (to reduce
clothes competition). Or one rationale for a consumption tax, or
incentives for saving. (A savings account is a socially invisible
thing. People can brag about how much they've got, but it's not
all that credible.) We are in a situation now much like the ball
game where one by one people start standing up to get a better
view. The first few people benefit. But eventually, everyone sees
only as well as they did when sitting, and their legs are all
tired. They need an announcer to get on the loudspeaker and tell
them all to sit back down. </p>

<p>It looks to me like we have gotten onto a faster and faster
consumer treadmill, working longer hours and depriving ourselves
of savings, public goods, and a healthy environment, in order to
keep this competition going. It's high time somebody told us all
to sit down and relax. The question is, how do we get people to
listen?</p>

<p>NOTE: I enjoyed your comments last week. Next week I will
present some evidence from the survey I have just conducted on
these issues. Have a nice holiday tomorrow. By the way, on our
last one day holiday--Veterans Day--I noticed the whole world was
shopping. In fact, near a new designer clothing outlet here, the
police had to close down the off ramp from the Interstate,
because the traffic to get to the mall was blocking up the whole
highway. How's that for American consumerism! </p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
