<blockquote>
<h2>LOL Forums</h2>
<p>LOL members read and write messages which accumulate in our Forums. These exchanges 
are serious and extensive, without flaming or other disruptive behavior.</p>
<p>A particularly nice thing about LOL forums is that LOL lets users do all reading, writing, and 
searching offline with very efficient tools. LOL Forums are also the vehicle we use for our 
online courses.</p>
<p>There are three alternative ways to access and use LOL forums (and Internet News Groups) 
from the LOL site:. </p>
<ul>
<li>You can do forum work inside your web browser window, literally never using 
anything other than Netscape or Microsoft Explorer, for ease of use.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>You can do it with the add-on News Group reader that comes with Netscape or 
Explorer, for greater functionality.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>You can do it with our special plug-in module, some screens from which are pictured 
here, for optimum functionality, if you are using windows.</li>
</ul>
<p><img src="../../images/frinde1.gif" align=bottom width=616 height=241></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p><img src="../../images/frinde2.gif" align=bottom width=590 height=350></p>
<blockquote>
<blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>&#160;</p>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>Forums are the heart of LOL. Below we include brief descriptions of <strong>some</strong> forums currently 
active on LOL. </p>
<p>A few of the sample of Forum names below are web links which lead to examples of forum 
messages. As the discussions are in-depth and these messages are in some cases from the 
middle of long running discussions, users may have some difficulty following the entirety of 
their references. Still, they give a good feeling for what goes on in LOL forums.</p>
<dl>
<dt><b>Activism</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for users to present information and reports about current activism, and to 
discuss activist projects and ideas. </dd>
<dt><b>Anarchy</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing anarchist philosophy and aims.</dd>
<dt><a href="azc.htm"><b>ChomskyChat</b></a></dt>
<dd>This forum has two respondants, Michael Albert (the Z part of the title) and Noam 
Chomsky (the C part of the title). Albert's role is to keep things moving when Chomsky 
is off traveling and can't respond. Generally, however, Noam answers queries once a 
week, and discussions proceed from there. </dd>
<dt><b>Campus</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing the politics of academia and of academics, and the campus 
experience more generally.</dd>
<dt><b>CurEvnt</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing current events and happenings of all kinds. Like current events in 
the fourth grade, but with a little more political consciousness at play. </dd>
<dt><b>CurrentZ</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing articles in the current issue of Z. </dd>
<dt><b>Ecopol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing ecological issues and green politics. </dd>
<dt><b>ForPol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing foreign policy issues</dd>
<dt><b>Gender</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing gender related issues of all kinds. Sexism, sexual preference, 
sexual practices, strategy, articles, books, behavior, whatever... </dd>
<dt><b>GenPhil</b></dt>
<dd>This is a kind of catch-all forum for discussing philosophical matters. There is no need 
for a political link. Anything that has general intellectual interest can be aired here.</dd>
<dt><b>Internet</b></dt>
<dd>This is a forum where people can introduce one another to internet sites and 
methodologies, discuss internet politics, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Hello</b></dt>
<dd>This is a forum where people can introduce themselves and ask introductory questions 
about the use of the system. It is also a place to ask how to get started, and to meet other 
people and strike up online friendships, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Help</b></dt>
<dd>We have various online help forums where users can get help with DOS, Windows, or 
Mac programs respectively, for LOL or otherwise, from knowledgable users. </dd>
<dt><b>Humor</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for people to share jokes, humourous material, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Labor</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing labor and union related issues. It is open for all to participate, 
but we hope that union activists and rank and file working people will bring up and 
develop views on labor issues. </dd>
<dt><a href="mark.htm"><b>Markets</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing the merits and debits of markets as institutions for economic 
allocation.</dd>
<dt><b>MediaPol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing mainstream media and its politics. How it works, what is going 
on in it, what to do about it, etc.</dd>
<dt><a href="movie.htm"><b>Movies</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for reviewing/discussing movies.</dd>
<dt><b>Music</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for reviewing/discussing contemporary music.</dd>
<dt><a href="parecon.htm"><b>Parecon</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing Participatory Economics (the non-market, non centrally planned) 
post capitalist economy proposed by Michael Albert and Robin Hahnel, as well as 
economic vision in general, and related strategic and visionary issues having to do with 
work, consumption, production, allocation. Albert and Hahnel participate actively. </dd>
<dt><b>PolEcon</b></dt>
<dd>A forum to discuss the political economy of the U.S. and of modern economies more 
generally. How do they work, what is the structure, what are their dynamics, and so on.</dd>
<dt><a href="popcult.htm"><b>PopCult</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussion of pop culture in general, and pop culture events as they unfold.</dd>
<dt><b>ProgPubs</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing alternative media and its politics. How it works, what is going 
on in it, what to do about it, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>R-Wing</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing the resurgence of right wing politics in the U.S.--its logic, 
dynamics, and what to do about it.</dd>
<dt><a href="race.htm"><b>Race</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing any issues bearing on race, racism, cultural visions for diverse 
communities, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Religion</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing religious ideas and issues, and religion and politics.</dd>
<dt><a href="schools.htm"><b>Schools</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussion of teaching policies, public schools, education, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>SexPol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing sexual politics, sexuality, and sexual political program.</dd>
<dt><b>Strategy</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing how to win a better world, or anything less comprehensive.</dd>
<dt><b>Youth</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing issues and ideas particularly relevant to or arising from the 
experiences of young people. </dd>
</dl>
<p>&#160; </p>
<h2>LOL Teleconferencing</h2>
<p>LOL also has a sophisticated teleconferencing system (like IRC chat but more robust and 
functional) for those interested in online dialogues. More, the system will support audio in 
the near future.</p>
<blockquote>
