<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>About parecon</title>
</head>

<body background="images/ideaback.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p><img src="images/idealine.gif" width="432" height="4"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h1 align="left"><img src="images/parecon.gif"
        width="235" height="72"></h1>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p align="left"><img src="images/ideaabt.gif" width="432"
height="30"></p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p>Participatory Economics is the name of a type of
        economy proposed as a desirable alternative to
        contemporary capitalism. The &quot;authors&quot; of this
        model, or vision, are Michael Albert and Robin Hahnel.
        the underlying values the economic vision seeks to
        implement are:</p>
        <dl>
            <dd><img src="images/ideadot.gif" width="20"
                height="20"> equity</dd>
            <dd><img src="images/ideadot.gif" width="20"
                height="20"> solidarity</dd>
            <dd><img src="images/ideadot.gif" width="20"
                height="20"> diversity</dd>
            <dd><img src="images/ideadot.gif" width="20"
                height="20"> participatory self management.</dd>
        </dl>
        <p>The online Participatory Economics Project is an
        effort to use telecommunications to refine and otherwise
        improve the parecon model, to disseminate information
        about it and build support for it, and to stimulate
        activism around the parecon vision and provide support
        for people trying to implement components of parecon now
        or to win changes in existing structures consistent with
        trying to implement parecon in the future.</p>
        <p>The various facets of the online Parecon project are
        mostly in an early conceptual stage, with much more work
        to be done. However, one author, also an editor of <em>Z
        Magazine</em>, Michael Albert, taught an online course on
        &quot;Developing Economic Vision,&quot; in the online
        school available through Left On Line. The purpose of the
        course was to collectively go through the process of
        conceptualizing an economic vision. The aim was to
        develop skills and concepts suitable to the task and
        adaptable, as well, to the task of conceptualizing vision
        for other aspects of social life. </p>
        <p>Albert posted a new lecture designed to provoke and
        sustain creative student participation each week for ten
        weeks. Each lecture contained many questions which
        students in the class discussed during the ensuing week,
        with Albert contributing, answering questions, etc. Then
        there would be a new lecture, including succinct answers
        to the many questions asked the prior week. </p>
        <p>While the lectures and discussions were aimed at
        developing skills and broad general principles, they also
        evolved a fairly comprehensive picture of the
        Participatory Economic vision.</p>
        <p>For now, the only thing we have to offer in the online
        Parecon Project is these lectures (though not the weekly
        discussion). They are included here as links to lectures
        1 - 10..</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
