<h2><img src="gifs/blhelp.gif" alt="ZNet HELP" align=top hspace=4 width=55 height=54> <img src="gifs/mdznet.gif" align=top hspace=4 width=148 height=75> <img src="gifs/lghelp.gif" align=top hspace=4 vspace=12 width=102 height=28> </h2>
<hr>
<p><a href="index.htm"><img src="gifs/smznet.gif" alt="ZNet | " align=middle border=0 hspace=4 width=73 height=37></a> <a href="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><img src="gifs/feedback.gif" alt="Feedback" align=middle border=0 hspace=4 width=90 height=46> </a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<p>If you are new to the World Wide Web (WWW), <strong>don't be intimidated! </strong>Most browsers (the programs you use to navigate 
the Web) indicate that an element of text is a <strong>hyperlink</strong> by underlining it. And most of the graphic elements on this site (if 
your browser displays them) are also links. Graphical browsers, like Mosaic and Netscape, allow you to follow links just 
by clicking on them with the mouse. Text based browsers, like Lynx, let you follow links through various keyboard 
schemes; consult the help facilities of your browser. When in doubt, click!--the Web is robust: you can't hurt it. </p>
<p>To use the World Wide Web effectively, unless you're already directly connected to the Internet, you need a PPP/SLIP 
connection, available through <a href="lbbs/index.htm">Left on Line</a>. </p>
<p>You'll also need a browser, program for viewing Web documents. <strong>Netscape is recommended</strong> for the best viewing of this 
site, and is available to <a href="http://home.mcom.com/comprod/mirror/index.html">download</a> at no charge from Netscape Communications Corporation, which is not affiliated with 
ZNet or LBBS. </p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Starting Points</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Here is a list of some links to WWW catalogs and other good starting points for browsing. </p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers/Internet/Beginner_s_Guides/"><b>Internet Beginner's Guides</b></a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.lm.com/~lmann/docs/easymosaic.html"><b>Easy Mosaic and Introductory Web Surfing</b></a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.sils.umich.edu/~fprefect/inet/using/html.html"><b>Starting to use the Web</b></a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/General/Internet/WWW/HTMLPrimer.html"><b>A Beginner's Guide to HTML</b></a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www-slis.lib.indiana.edu/Internet/programmer-page.html"><b>A Primer for creating Web Resources</b></a> </li>
<li><a href="http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/reports/Servers-web.html"><b>Spinning the Web: Setting Up World Wide Web Server</b></a> </li>
</ul>
<p><a><b>Yahoo</b></a> is the name of a service that provides excellent guidance through the WWW, including useful listings, links, searh 
options, etc. etc. Connect with them if you want to do some serious browsing or researching on the World Wide Web. </p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
