<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#3A0D9F" vlink="#AF0475" alink="#0E7F09">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=149><a href="#C1"><img src="wild_c1.gif" alt="Starting Points" align=bottom border=0 width=149 height=34></a><br>
<a href="#C2"><img src="wild_c2.gif" alt="Left Links" align=bottom border=0 width=149 height=47></a><br>
<a href="#C3"><img src="wild_c3.gif" alt="Interesting Places" align=bottom border=0 width=149 height=34></a><br>
<a href="tools.htm"><img src="wild_c4.gif" alt="Internet Tools" align=bottom border=0 width=149 height=31></a><br>
<a href="about.htm"><img src="wild_c5.gif" alt="LOL Info" align=bottom border=0 width=149 height=35></a> </td><td width=328><img src="lolguide.gif" alt="The Left On Line Guide to the Internet" align=bottom width=328 height=181> </td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<h1 align=center>Welcome to the Web!</h1>
<p>If you are new to the World Wide Web, <b>don't be intimidated!</b> The Web is simply a large number of pages of text 
and graphics that are linked together with <b>hyperlinks</b>. Most browsers (the programs you use to navigate the Web) 
indicate that an element of text is a hyperlink by underlining it (as in the link: <a href="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</a>). And many graphic elements 
(if your browser displays them) are also links. Graphical browsers, like Netscape and Microsoft Explorer, allow 
you to follow links just by clicking on them with the mouse. Text based browsers, like Lynx, let you follow links 
using your keyboard. Don't worry about clicking on links you're not sure of -- you can't cause any harm to the 
Web. </p>
<p>Although the easiest way to learn is by doing, here is a list of some links to starting points for learning more 
about browsing. Whenever you click on a link you will go to the associated site. You can always come back here 
by using the back up a page option or the Return to Home option on your browser. </p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.yahoo.com/text/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/Information_and_Documentation/Beginner_s_Guides/"><b>Internet Beginner's Guides</b></a><b> </b></li>
<li><a href="http://www.eit.com/web/www.guide/"><b>A Guide to Cyberspace</b></a> </li>
</ul>
<p>If you want to create your own web pages or create your own site, you need to understand a little about the 
underlying language of Web design. Here are some good places to begin:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/General/Internet/WWW/HTMLPrimer.html"><b>A Beginner's Guide to HTML</b></a><b> </b></li>
<li><a href="http://home.netscape.com/assist/net_sites/index.html"><b>Creating Net Sites</b></a><b> </b></li>
</ul>
<hr size=3 width=20%>
<h2 align=center>Starting Points For Web Surfing</h2>
<p align=center>There are two basic ways to travel the Web. You can have something in mind that you want to find and use a 
search engine to look for related sites and pages. Or you can browse by going to a site with lots of interesting 
links and following those that strike your fancy, then continuing to new links, and so on. Here we give you a start 
with both these approaches by indicating: </p>
<div align=center><center>
<table>
<tr><td valign=top width=25%><b>Good Sites To Search From:</b> <ul>
<li><a href="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.excite.com/">Excite</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">Alta Vista</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.opentext.com/">OpenText</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.webcrawler.com/">WebCrawler</a> </li>
</ul>
</td><td valign=top width=25%><b>Good Sites To Start Browsing From:</b> <ul>
<li><a href="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.shareworld.com/">ShareWorld</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/">The Progressive Directory at IGC</a> </li>
<li><a href="http://www.webactive.com/webactive/">WebActive</a> </li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<hr size=3 width=20%>
<p align=center><font size=4><i>Left On Line's Guide to</i></font> </p>
<h2 align=center>Left Links</h2>
<p align=center><font size=2>This list focuses on Left-oriented publications and activist resources. Many of these sites were culled from </font><a href="http://www.webactive.com/webactive/"><font size=2><b>WebActive</b></font></a><font size=2> and </font><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/"><font size=2><b>IGC</b></font></a><font size=2> 
sites.</font> </p>
<table>
<tr><td valign=top width=45%><dl>
<dt><a href="http://mxe115.rh.psu.edu/index.htm">Action Center Homepage</a> </dt>
<dd>Billed as an &quot;activists' center for training in 
organizing and networking,&quot; it is a collection of very 
good material (plus some links) to aid the progressive 
activist. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://hoshi.cic.sfu.ca/adbusters/">Adbusters' Culture Jammers Headquarters</a> </dt>
<dd>A great site done by Adbusters, a group that fights fire 
with fire. See their ads that fly in the face of billion 
dollar images. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com">The Atlantic</a> </dt>
<dd>Since 1857, the Atlantic has provided intellectual 
coverage of politics, society, culture and the arts. The 
magazine, which falls somewhere between the Nation 
and Harpers, presents a Web site full of its writing, 
and now offers the Election Connection. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://MediaFilter.org/MFF/CAQ_Contents.html">CovertAction Quarterly </a></dt>
<dd>CovertAction Quarterly is a publication devoted to 
human rights and uncovering covert activity. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/crossroads/">Crossroads</a> </dt>
<dd>A magazine aimed at rebuilding an effective left 
political current in U.S. politics. Published by the 
<a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/crossroads/ises.html">Institute for Social and Economic Studies</a>. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/dollars/">Dollars &amp; Sense</a> </dt>
<dd>A magazine that explains the workings of the U.S. and 
international economies and provides left 
persepctives on current economic affairs. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.earthisland.org/">Earth Island Institute</a> </dt>
<dd>Run by feisty environmentalists, Earth Island Institute 
has a site which includes full-text newsletters, and 
information on thirty projects related to everything 
from from dolphin, whales and sea turtles to 
environmental justice to rethinking paper. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.essential.org/EI.html">Essential Information</a> </dt>
<dd>Founded by Ralph Nader, EI provides provocative 
information to the public on important topics 
neglected by the mass media and policy makers. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.fair.org/fair/">Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting </a></dt>
<dd>FAIR documents media bias towards corporations and 
their insensitivity to the interests of labor, women, 
minorities, and other public interest groups. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://iww.org/">IWW Resource</a> </dt>
<dd>The site of the International Workers of the World. It 
contains everything from information about the IWW 
to links related to Earth First! and the striking 
journalists of the Detroit News. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.bypass.com/~N_E_Research/left/">Jay's Leftist and &quot;Progressive&quot; Internet Resources 
Directory </a></dt>
<dd>Wow! Jay has put together quite a list, and it is well 
organized. It's enough to keep you busy for weeks. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.channel1.com/users/jay/welcome.htm">Madness</a> </dt>
<dd>Madness is a group of politically-minded 
twentysomethings who present episodic, subversive 
fiction. The result is, well, Madness. </dd>
</dl>
</td><td valign=top width=45%><dl>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.org/MakingContact/">Making Contact</a> </dt>
<dd>A new national radio program that gives 
listeners information they need to take action. It 
is produced by Norman Solomon and David 
Barsamian. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.mojones.com/">The MoJo Wire </a></dt>
<dd>The MoJo Wire is Mother Jones Magazine's 
interactive WWW publication. The MoJo Wire 
offers a feast of information for progressives. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.thenation.com/">The Nation </a></dt>
<dd>No need to browse the news stand for The 
Nation, for it is always in the same place on the 
Web. Feast on the digital edition of this 
hard-hitting progressive publication. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.pacifica.org/">Pacifica </a></dt>
<dd>Balance your Pacifica listening with some 
Pacifica reading. This site serves mostly to 
inform you of the organization, its mission and 
its contents. There are some listening options, 
including out-takes of an interview with Noam 
Chomsky. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.ran.org/ran/">Rainforest Action Network </a></dt>
<dd>RAN is a decade old organization dedicated to 
protecting rainforests and the rights of the people 
who work in them. The RAN web page is 
exquisitely designed, but may be rough on 14.4k 
modem users. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.seac.org/">SEAC</a> </dt>
<dd>Website for the Student Environmental Action 
Coalition, with over 1,500 high school and 
college groups in all fifty states. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.socialpolicy.org/">Social Policy</a> </dt>
<dd>A quarterly magazine that address politics, 
culture and &quot;movements.&quot; Stylish yet simple 
layout and diverse content. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.lglobal.com/TAO/">The Media Collective</a> </dt>
<dd>A rich collection of anarchist resources </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.utne.com/">The Utne Lens</a> </dt>
<dd>The Utne Lens is the Utne Reader's online 
publication. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.webactive.com/">WebActive</a> </dt>
<dd>Your weekly source on progressive activism 
online. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.lbbs.org/zmag/index.htm">Z Magazine</a> </dt>
<dd>Z Magazine is a provocative alternative monthly 
magazine which boasts Noam Chomsky among 
its frequent contributors. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</a> </dt>
<dd>Your starting point for such valuable resources 
as the <a href="http://www.worldmedia.com/archive/">Noam Chomsky Archive</a>, <a href="http://www.lbbs.org/zmag.index.htm">Z Magazine</a>, the 
Left On Line Bulletin Board System, Left On 
Line University and the Z Media Institute. </dd>
</dl>
</td></tr>
</table>
<hr size=3 width=20%>
<h2 align=center>Some Interesting Places To Visit</h2>
<p align=center><font size=2>These sites were culled from the much larger list available at the </font><a href="http://www.webactive.com/webactive/"><font size=2><b>WebActive</b></font></a><font size=2> site.</font> </p>
<table>
<tr><td valign=top><dl>
<dt><a href="http://www.cais.com/agm/">The Abortion Rights Activist Home Page</a> </dt>
<dd>The Abortions Rights Activist Home Page is a 
new and evolving site intended to provide 
information to the pro-choice community. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.ns.doe.ca//aeb/ssd/Acid/acidFAQ.html">Acid Rain FAQ</a> </dt>
<dd>The Acid Rain FAQ comes courtesy of 
Environment Canada's A Primer on 
Environmental Citizenship. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.aflcio.org">AFL-CIO</a> </dt>
<dd>The AFL-CIO web site hosts information about 
the AFL-CIO and resources valuable to anyone 
interested in labor. </dd>
<dt><a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/race/aanews">African American News Service</a> </dt>
<dd>The African American News Service is 
sponsored by the Institute for Global 
Communications and serves as an alternative 
source for news relating to the African American 
community. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.anc.org.za/">African National Congress Home Page</a> </dt>
<dd>The African National Congress has a stunning 
web site complete with links to other South 
African resources. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.aclu.org">American Civil Liberties Union</a> </dt>
<dd>The American Civil Liberties Union has taken the 
Web by storm with its Freedom Network. There's 
too much to describe here. Just go there and 
spend a day or two. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.apn.com/">American Political Network</a> </dt>
<dd>Do you want to get &quot;virtually&quot; inside the 
Beltway? Then the APN is the place to be. Such 
offerings as The Hotline, American Healthline, 
and Greenwire, each offered daily, will ensure 
that you never miss a beat. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.io.org/amnesty/">Amnesty International Online</a> </dt>
<dd>Amnesty International is now on the web. Among 
the site's highlights: AI's 1994 country reports, 
details on current Amnesty projects, and links to 
other human rights resources on the Internet. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://envirolink.org/arrs/index.html">Animal Rights Resource Site</a> </dt>
<dd>The Animal Rights Resource Site maintains a 
wealth of information about animal rights ... the 
photos are not for children. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.enews.com:80/magazines/body/">Body Politic</a> </dt>
<dd>Body Politic is a pro-choice magazine ironically 
based in Binghamton, New York -- the birthplace 
of Operation Rescue. Its web site offers gopher 
access to some articles as well as information on 
subscribing. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.the-body-shop.com/">The Body Shop</a> </dt>
<dd>The business of the Body Shop is the manufacture 
and retail of beauty products. At the same time, 
the Body Shop is concerned with being a good 
citizen of the world. The Body Shop's Web site 
currently focuses on the latter task... </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.cais.com/agf/cwindex.htm">Catholic Worker Home Page</a> </dt>
<dd>This is an unofficial page done by an admirer of 
the Catholic Worker movement. The movement, 
born during the Great Depression, aims to 
provide food, clothing, shelter and welcome the 
needy in poor areas, both urban and rural. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://latino.sscnet.ucla.edu/">Chicano/Latino Network</a> </dt>
<dd>The Chicano/Latino Network (CLNet), is a 
&quot;general Latino focused Internet site serving all 
segments of the community.&quot; It is based at UCLA 
and offers a wide variety of information, ranging 
from resources for academic research on Latino 
issues to job listings. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.dnai.com/~children/">Children Now </a></dt>
<dd>Children Now is a non-partisan non-profit 
organization dedicated to protecting the rights and 
welfare of children. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.cpsr.org/home.html">Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility </a></dt>
<dd>CPSR, which recently revamped its web site, is a 
non-profit organization concerned with the effects 
of computers on society. Of particular interest on 
the CPSR home page is a page of articles about 
gender issues and computing. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.essential.org/CMEP/">Critical Mass Energy Project </a></dt>
<dd>Promotes energy conservation and tracks 
government activities related to such issues as 
nuclear power, radioactive waste, renewable 
energy and fuel efficiency. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.dsausa.org/">Democratic Socialists of America</a> </dt>
<dd>The largest socialist organization in the United 
States, and the principal U.S. affiliate of the 
Socialist International. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.doonesbury.com/">The Doonesbury Electronic Town Hall </a></dt>
<dd>Doonesbury, the witty and poignant cartoon by 
Gary Trudeau, has arrived on the Web and it has 
a mission. In addition to daily political 
information, flashbacks to historic news and 
Doonesbury cartoons, the site hosts a section 
called Get Involved. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/econet/">EcoNet @igc</a> </dt>
<dd>EcoNet is a large directory of environmental 
sites, maintained by the Institute for Global 
Communications. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.eff.org/">Electronic Frontier Foundation</a> </dt>
<dd>EFF is a leading non-profit civil liberties 
organization working in the public interest to 
protect privacy, free expression, and access to 
online resources and information. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.envirolink.org/issues/esa/">Endangered Species Act On-Line Resource Guide </a></dt>
<dd>The Endangered Species Act is a critical, 
controversial and confusing piece of legislation 
that serves to prevent human actions from pushing 
animals and plants into extinction. The on-line 
resource guide is a one-stop shop for information 
about the Act, and it encourages you to play a part 
in preventing the Act from following the route of 
the dodo and the passenger pigeon. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.edf.org">Environmental Defense Fund </a></dt>
<dd>EDF is a non-profit organization which aims to 
stop environmental pollution by encouraging 
business, labor, government, and citizen groups to 
cooperate and identify practical policies to 
protect the environment. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.enviroindustry.com/">Environmental Industry</a> </dt>
<dd>This site hosts information on businesses that 
provide environmental products and/or services. 
It lists companies, organizations and publications. 
It also includes a calendar of related events. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.webdirectory.com/">The Environmental Organization WebDirectory </a></dt>
<dd>If you went to one of this directory's listed sites 
every day, you'd finish in about three years. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.ewg.org/">Environmental Working Group</a> </dt>
<dd>The EWG is a project of the Tides Foundation. 
The site serves to distribute the organization's 
reports on such subjects as pesticides, pollution 
and farm subsidies. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.feminist.org/">The Feminist Majority Foundation</a> </dt>
<dd>The Feminist Majority heads to the Net with the 
Women's Web World, a site packed with 
information and calls for action, all pertaining to 
promoting a women's rights. </dd>
</dl>
</td><td valign=top><dl>
<dt><a href="http://www.feminist.com/">Feminist.Com</a> </dt>
<dd>The richness of the tree that greets the visitor to this 
site is an indication of the resources presented 
within. Let Feminist.com guide you to health 
information, activism and much more. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.gdn.org/">Global Democracy Network</a> </dt>
<dd>A searchable stockpile of documents related to 
international human rights. Though human rights 
issues is the focus of this site, it also includes links to 
governmental information of nearly 30 nations. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.greenpeace.org/">Greenpeace International</a> </dt>
<dd>This is the official WWW site of Greenpeace, and it's 
looking better and better. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.house.gov/democrats/welcome.html">House Democrats Home Page </a></dt>
<dd>Rep. Richard Gephardt, Democratic minority leader, 
has established the House Democrats Home Page 
which offers updates on current legislation, profiles 
of Democratic leaders, and press releases. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/hr/">Human Rights @igc</a> </dt>
<dd>This web page, hosted by the Institute for Global 
Communications, includes information related to US 
and international human rights. </dd>
<dt><a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org/11/headlines">IGC's News Headlines </a></dt>
<dd>The gopher site of the Institute for Global 
Communications maintains news headlines and 
articles on topics not normally covered by the 
mainstream press. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.alternet.org/an/">Institute for Alternative Journalism</a> </dt>
<dd>An organization based in San Francisco that is an 
&quot;advocate for diversity of news opinions and 
analysis within the media.&quot; </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/">The Institute for Global Communications</a> </dt>
<dd>IGC links together different elements of the 
progressive community through communications 
technology. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.isoc.org/">The Internet Society </a></dt>
<dd>As described on the site, &quot;The Internet Society is a 
non governmental International organization for 
global cooperation and coordination for the Internet 
and its internetworking technologies and 
applications. &quot; </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.zen.org/~brendan/kids.html">The Kids on the Web </a></dt>
<dd>This site includes seemingly-endless links to 
locations on the 'Net related to kids. Games, books 
and educational resources abound. All ages will have 
fun and learn. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/labornet/">LaborNet </a></dt>
<dd>LaborNet is one of the five networks of the <a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/">Institute 
for Global Communications</a>. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.lbbs.org/lolu.htm">Left On Line University</a> </dt>
<dd>The Left On Line University (LOLU) &quot;provides three 
semesters per year of university level, 15-week 
courses in political, social, economic, historical, and 
activist topics.&quot; Noam Chomsky, Holly Sklar, and 
Howard Zinn are among LOLU's faculty. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.loc.gov/">Library of Congress Information Services</a> </dt>
<dd>This is the WWW resource of the Library of 
Congress. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.bluemarble.net/~mitch/groups.html">Mitch's Environmental Action Page</a> </dt>
<dd>Mitch has compiled a wonderful assortment of action 
items and information on dioxins, PCBs, other toxics, 
as well as general environmental issues. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.politicalindex.com">The National Political Index</a> </dt>
<dd>A new addition to political archives and indices. But 
this one could soon become the definitive list. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.npr.org">National Public Radio </a></dt>
<dd>NPR's web site offers information about NPR and 
newsheadlines in RealAudio format. (Note: you can 
access NPR audio over the Internet daily at the 
<a href="http://www.RealAudio.com">RealAudio</a> web site.) </dd>
<dt><a href="http://ukanaix.cc.ukans.edu/~marc/native_main.html">NativeWeb </a></dt>
<dd>NativeWeb maintains resources about native peoples 
as well as links to other relevant sites. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.newparty.org/">The New Party </a></dt>
<dd>The New Party is just what the name implies. It is a 
progressive alternative to the two-party system, 
promoting an agenda that includes campaign finance 
reform, improving public schools, universal voter 
registration, creating family supporting jobs without 
wrecking the environment, raising the minimum wage 
and universal access to health care. For now it is 
focusing on local offices, but it has high hopes. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.outnow.com">OutNOW! Alive </a></dt>
<dd>One of the best gay sites and publications available 
on the Net. Its excellent contents provides a unifying 
force for the highly-dispersed gay community. </dd>
<dt><a href="gopher://gopher.brown.edu:70/11/brown/studinfo/studact/oxfam/hungorg/oxfam">Oxfam </a></dt>
<dd>Since 1970, Oxfam America has been working with 
poor people throughout the world to combat hunger. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.peacenet.apc.org/peacenet/">PeaceNet @igc</a> </dt>
<dd>PeaceNet is a world-wide computer network 
&quot;serving organizations and individuals working for 
positive change in the area of peace.&quot; PeaceNet is 
maintained by the Insitute for Global 
Communications. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.politicsusa.com/">PoliticsUSA </a></dt>
<dd>Election 96 is coming! Watch it unfold on 
PoliticsUSA. Daily news, campaign analyses and a 
rundown of candidates' positions on key issues. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.prognet.com/prognet/">Progressive Networks, Inc.</a> </dt>
<dd>Progressive Networks is the creator of RealAudio 
audio-on-demand software for the Internet. In 
addition to RealAudio, PN aims to bring the 
networking power of the Internet to bear on social 
and political issues. PN is the sponsor of What's 
New in Activism Online. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.rednet.co.uk:80/redpepper/">Red Pepper </a></dt>
<dd>Red Pepper Magazine brings the UK's cultural and 
political left to you. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.clark.net/pub/jeffd/index.html">The Right Side of the Web </a></dt>
<dd>The Right Side of the Web is one of the most popular 
conservative sites on the World Wide Web. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.sierraclub.org">Sierra Club </a></dt>
<dd>The Sierra Club web site offers information on the 
Sierra Club, its local chapters, and action alerts. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.house.gov/mbr_dir/membr_dir.html">U.S. House of Representatives - Member Directory</a> </dt>
<dd>The U.S. House of Representatives member directory 
allows you to easily find out who your 
representatives are and how to contact them. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.ucsusa.org/">Union of Concerned Scientists</a> </dt>
<dd>Good science usually speaks the truth. The Union of 
Concerned Scientists gathers the best science in 
order to defend peace and environmental protection. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.well.com/">The WELL</a> </dt>
<dd>Be sure to take a trip to The WELL. Its <a href="http://www.well.com/Community/">community 
pages</a> and its <a href="http://gopher.well.com:70/">gopher server</a> offer a fantastic wealth of 
links and information. While you are there, check out 
the <a href=" http://gopher.well.sf.ca.us:70/1s/Politics/activist.tools">Activist Toolkit</a>. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/">White House</a> </dt>
<dd>This is Bill Clinton's home. </dd>
<dt><a href="http://www.wald.com/">Working Assets Long Distance </a></dt>
<dd>Working Assets Long Distance provides 
long-distance telephone service and contributes a 
portion of its revenue to progressive non-profits. </dd>
</dl>
</td></tr>
</table>
