<html>

<head>
<title>MNay 96: Herman; Insecurity State</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#00CC00" vlink="#000055" alink="#00FF00">
<h2>from the pages of<img src="../../../Program Files/Microsoft FrontPage/pages/zarticle2.htm.tem/../../../../NavGold/Program/oldsmzma.gif" alt="../" align=top hspace=4 width=108 height=37> </h2>
<hr>
<p><a href="../index.htm"><img src="../../../Program Files/Microsoft FrontPage/pages/zarticle2.htm.tem/../../../../NavGold/Program/smzmag.gif" alt="../Z Magazine | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=108 height=37></a><a href="../../help.htm"><img src="../../../Program Files/Microsoft FrontPage/pages/zarticle2.htm.tem/../../../../NavGold/Program/help.gif" alt="../HELP" align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=56 height=54></a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h2 align=center>From Security To Insecurity State </h2>
<p><em><strong>By Edward S. Herman </strong></em></p>
<p>During the Cold War the United States built an immense national security apparatus, supposedly to counter the 
military threat posed by the Soviet Union, but in fact serving larger goals. Curiously, while the public was 
made anxious about possible war and nuclear incineration, this was a time of relative economic security for the 
population at large. In the post-Cold War years, by contrast, with the military threat no longer credible, 
economic insecurity has increased markedly and we have moved from a security state to an insecurity state. </p>
<p>The security state era was characterized by the development of a tacit social contract between labor and 
capital, the maintenance of high levels of employment under a system of military Keynesianism, and some 
sharing of the gains of technological progress. An important element underlying the relatively peaceful class 
relations was the Cold War and competition with socialist ideas and systems claiming to be socialist. As with 
a non-union company in an economy with significant unionization, where the company management feels 
compelled to treat its workers well to keep unions out, so the leaders of U.S. capitalism felt the need to do the 
same in order to reduce the attractiveness of an alternative model. </p>
<p>With the collapse of the major socialist states and widespread setbacks to social democracy, the material and 
ideological threat of socialism receded. There was no longer a need to compete for the loyalty of workers; the 
vision of an alternative route in which communal interests, equality, and attention to the needs of all citizens 
was the focus, had been at least temporarily removed. Add to this the force and power of a rapidly globalizing 
market system, its political strength and increased ability to constrain social democratic policies, and the 
associated weakening of the labor movement, and the stage was set for the unilateral abrogation of the social 
contract and renewal of open class warfare. Larger and larger circles of workers became subject to 
&#147;reengineering&#148; of the workplace, essentially without defenses; vast numbers were fired, and still larger 
numbers saw their wages and benefits stagnate or decline. Meanwhile, the reengineering elite, owners of 
capital, and banking-security fraternity prospered, and income inequality and polarization increased steadily. 
Welcome to the insecurity state. </p>
<p><strong>Ideological Reengineering </strong></p>
<p>The security state was based on an ideology that focused on the military threat of socialism, as well as the 
inherent economic and political superiority of capitalism. Anticommunism was the centerpiece of security state 
ideology. But socialism had to be seen as inherently aggressive and expansionist; otherwise, how justify arming 
to the teeth, surrounding socialist states with military bases, organizing &#147;contra&#148; armies to attack them (the 
Soviet Union, China, Angola, Cuba, Nicaragua, and others), and engaging in unremitting efforts to destabilize 
each and every one of them? Reams of political and academic propaganda were therefore devoted to proving 
the expansionist tendencies of socialism and the imperative need to &#147;contain&#148; them. (Liberal academic John 
Gaddis explained that the Soviet Union was &#147;perceived&#148; by the West as constituting a &#147;challenge,&#148; which he 
seemed to regard as an adequate justification for the multi-leveled attacks that began with active support of the 
counter-revolutionary White Russian armies and even Western invasion forces.) </p>
<p>Even tiny Nicaragua, under external attack by the U.S. and its proxy forces, was alleged by U.S. officials to be 
pursuing a &#147;revolution without frontiers&#148; (based on a deliberate misreading of a speech by Sandinista minister 
Tomas Borges), and Nicaragua (like Guatemala in 1954) was falsely alleged to be a Moscow proxy and thus 
evidence of Soviet expansionism in action. (This baloney was even disseminated by purported &#147;leftists&#148; like 
Fred Halliday, who, like the Pope in Managua this past February, claimed that the U.S. aggression against 
Nicaragua was really a battle between East and West. Halliday writing in 1989, about Nicaragua among other 
struggles, said &#147;the course of these disputes is to a great extent still formed by East-West rivalry.&#148; The Pope 
said that Nicaragua had been &#147;a shooting gallery of the superpowers,&#148; a lie as only one superpower was 
shooting). These incessant attacks forced the poor and struggling socialist countries to waste resources on arms 
and reinforced their worst political tendencies; but if the West's policies were merely &#147;containing aggression,&#148; 
any systematic effects on socialist development could be (and were) blamed on socialism, not Western 
aggression. </p>
<p>Western ideology and anticommunism also rested on the alleged naturalness and inevitability of the market 
system -- based in turn on humanity's &#147;propensity to truck, barter, and exchange&#148; in Adam Smith's famous 
phrase. Communal systems and especially state-sponsored and state-run activities were unnatural, and when 
heavily used put societies on the &#147;road to serfdom.&#148; (The counter-argument, effectively made by Karl Polanyi 
in <em>The Great Transformation</em>, is that the unnaturalness and destructive consequences of an unconstrained 
market are precisely what has caused welfare states to emerge in country after country, to contain and repair 
free market damage.) </p>
<p>With the collapse of socialism, the ideologists have shifted the emphasis from socialist aggression and gulags 
to the &#147;miracle of the market&#148; (Reagan), although there are periodic dredgings from Soviet archives as 
reminders of socialist crimes and Western leftist naivet&lt;@233&gt;. The ideologues have two advantages in 
scoring these cheap points: only Soviet secret police records are open, not those of the U.S.; and the ideologues 
(Will, Kraut-hammer, Limbaugh, etc.) can pontificate without having to contend with rebuttals. Readers of <em>Z 
Magazine </em>will be interested to know that in one of the rare cases where an establishment ideologue, in this 
case Richard Perle, was induced to participate in an open debate with Noam Chomsky, at Ohio State 
University in 1988, the tape of this encounter reveals that Perle was confuted on virtually every point and left 
speechless. </p>
<p>New World Order ideology rests on an obfuscation of ends and means. That is, while the ultimate objective of 
the economic order is said to be maximizing human happiness and satisfaction -- implicitly for all members of 
society -- this end has become subordinated to the preferred means of achieving it: namely, private markets 
operating virtually without government interference. But these preferred means happen to serve well a tiny 
global elite, so that the devotion to private markets as means is actually a cover for a real but hidden goal. The 
&#147;problem&#148; for the Swiss Guards of politics, media, and academia is how to rationalize and sell policies that 
serve a narrow class interest and fail systematically to accomplish their purported end. </p>
<p>Furthermore, the purr word &#147;freedom&#148; has come to connote, first, and sometimes exclusively, the freedom of 
business to do its thing, or as Steve Forbes expressed it, &#147;the right to spend your money anywhere in the world 
on whatever you wanted.&#148; This is why the editors of the <em>Wall Street Journal</em> and numerous economists have 
considered fascists and authoritarians like Pinochet and Salinas great statesmen. Of course the apologists argue 
that even if free markets are not producing political freedom now, they will surely do so at some future date; 
but what patience they display at the sometimes very lengthy and murderous cleansing operations of their 
totalitarian-free enterprise friends. How inconsistently they argued that the beauty of NAFTA was that it 
&#147;locked Mexico in&#148; to a free market path that the Mexican people might reject if they had a democratic choice. </p>
<p>But up to this point such issues have been muted. Only a Republican right-wing extremist like Buchanan can 
raise the economic/class issue in a twisted form, be heard, briefly, before he is hustled off the scene, and impel 
the mainstream media to put up multi-part personal interest accounts of the suffering of ordinary citizens. But 
for the dominant institutions and mainstream intellectuals, the answer remains: there is no other option but 
&#147;freedom,&#148; so let us privatize further, shrink the government and get the budget in balance, remove the burden 
of dependency from the backs of the poor, and make life more comfortable for the business community so that it 
will have an incentive to create jobs. </p>
<p><em>Serving the Insecurity State</em> </p>
<p>The economists have played their usual supporting role in backing up the preferences and demands of the 
powerful. It should be noted, of course, that there are quite a few economists who dissent from the mainstream 
consensus, but their voices are only rarely heard in the propaganda system. Their marginalization is aided by 
the fact that the &#147;conservative labyrinth&#148; (John Saloma, <em>Ominous Politics: The New Conservative Labyrinth</em>, 
Hill and Wang, 1984) -- with Olin, the Hoover Institution, and the American Enterprise Institute at the center of 
a network of corporate funded thinktanks -- funds a large number of proper thinking economists, helps get them 
accredited, their books and Op Ed columns published, and their opinions heard in the mainstream media. The 
dominant pundits are part of this network and push its preferred ideas, and the mainstream media accepts the 
labyrinth's &#147;experts&#148; while filtering out dissenting experts and messages. The Economic Policy Institute, which 
produces well researched but left-of-center analyses, is cited much less often by the press than the American 
Enterprise Institute, and is regularly referred to in the <em>New York Times</em> as &#147;labor supported.&#148; The paper's 
reporters never mention that AEI is corporate supported. </p>
<p>The mainstream economists have joined the Swiss Guards for a number of reasons: they are members of the 
elite, so that their alignment with the dominant class -- and against the working class majority -- on issues like 
NAFTA is comprehensible partly on that elemental ground. Class interest may also help explain the mainstream 
complaisance in the face of the sharp increase in inequality and immiseration of very large numbers of people. 
The leading economists are prospering, and, as noted, the conservative labyrinth pays well for cultivating 
sound thoughts, so that on Chicago School Gary Becker's logic -- that everything can be explained by the 
economic motive -- joining the Swiss Guards is a sound investment of personal capital on the part of 
economists. Large numbers also serve as paid consultants to private businesses, helping them invest and deal 
with regulators. These economists are literal employees of the corporate system, as are those working for the 
World Bank and IMF. </p>
<p>The economists also want to be practical, and in the New World Order, with George Soros and the banks ready 
to flee in the face of dreaded &#147;populist&#148; policies, and the dominant political parties unable to serve majority 
interests because of Golden Rule (Ferguson, <em>Golden Rule: The Investment Theory of Party Competition and 
the Logic of Money-Driven Political Systems</em>, University of Chicago, 1995), &#147;practical&#148; means doing nothing 
upsetting to the monied interests. The work of liberal Stanford economist Paul Krugman illustrates the 
paralyzing effect of subordination to the practical. In his <em>The Age of Diminished Expectations</em> he states that the 
huge increase in inequality in the Reagan years is the &#147;central fact&#148; and problem of the era, but he makes no 
recommendation to rectify the problem -- the trend toward greater inequality &#147;appears politically out of 
bounds;&#148; the problem of poverty &#147;has basically exhausted the patience of the general public.&#148; In fact, polls 
have consistently shown that a majority of the public would like to do something about income distribution; but 
the golden rulers, whose gains rest heavily on the losses of the population, don't -- and this feeds into the 
media, the political system, and by the route of an alleged political unfeasibility, to this practical economist. </p>
<p>The &#147;natural rate of unemployment&#148; is also a tool of the &#147;practical&#148; economist and servant of the status quo. 
Here again, Krugman takes a position that precludes the economy serving ordinary citizens. In his article &#147;Stay 
on Their Backs,&#148; in the <em>New York Times Magazine</em> of February 4, 1996, he poses as a liberal opponent of the 
supply-siders who think growth can be stimulated by cheap money. He rebuts these right-wing populists by 
bringing to bear the &#147;natural rate of unemployment,&#148; which at 5.5-6 percent is alleged to be at its limit, so that 
easy money would create inflation, etc. He even cites another liberal economist, Alan Blinder, as supporting 
this conservative position. The most interesting thing about his piece, however, is that Krugman once again 
surrenders to institutional necessity -- having proven to his own satisfaction that expansionary macro-policy is 
unworkable, he says nothing about how the mass distress endemic to the insecurity state is to be alleviated. By 
inference, this is the best of all possible (i.e., practical) worlds; which is to say, liberal economics is 
completely bankrupt. (Liberal textbooks in economics today regularly give great weight and status to the 
&#147;natural rate,&#148; rarely discuss institutional changes that would permit a low rate of unemployment while 
controlling inflation, and they never dismiss it as a mystical and unverifiable instrument of conservative 
policy.) </p>
<p><strong>The Devolution of Economics </strong></p>
<p>Economics has devolved badly over recent decades. Although the threat of macro-instability on a global scale 
has increased with the globalization of money markets, the enormous scale of speculation and new and 
complicated financial instruments, and the absence of a global central bank, there has been great complaisance 
in mainstream economics, and in Chicago School circles a regression of macro-theory to a belief that Say's 
Law (&#147;supply creates its own demand&#148;) and rational market forces make for inherent stabilizing properties in a 
free market system. Worry about monopoly and market power has diminished, and economists opposing 
concentration and centralization trends have not been audible. On income distribution, liberal economist James 
Tobin explained back in 1966 that &#147;the fire has gone out of this one,&#148; and Krugman agrees in 1992 on grounds 
of practicality. The powerful conservative economists couldn't care less, and some like Harvard's (and Hoover 
Institution's) Robert Barro even put a positive gloss on increasing inequality (&#147;Inequality and Its Charms,&#148; Wall 
Street Journal, Feb. 10, 1993). </p>
<p>The fire has also gone out of economists' concern with negative externalities and public goods, both of which 
are increasingly important in a world of advanced chemistry, technology, pressure on natural resources and 
ecology, and interdependence. The triumphant market does not want these market failures and bases for public 
ownership and regulation to be discussed, so the mainstream media and economists have put this set of issues 
on the back burner as well. </p>
<p><em>Edward S. Herman is a regular contributor to Z Magazine.</em></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
