<html>

<head>
<title>ShareWorld Community Page</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="images/blutxtr3.jpg" bgcolor="#A4B1B9">
<h1><font color="#0000A0"><font size=7><em><strong>ShareWorld Community</strong></em></font></font></h1>
<p><a href="swindex.htm"><img src="images/bhome.gif" alt="[Home Icon]" align=bottom border=0 width=56 height=14></a><a href="news.htm"><img src="images/bnews.gif" alt="[What's New Icon]" align=bottom border=0 width=58 height=14></a><a href="serv01.htm"><img src="images/bservs.gif" alt="[Products Icon]" align=bottom border=0 width=57 height=14></a><a href="feedback.htm"><img src="images/bfeed.gif" alt="[Feedback Icon]" align=bottom border=0 width=59 height=14></a></p>
<p><img src="images/div.gif" alt="[HRule Image]" align=bottom width=465 height=7> </p>
<h2>ShareWorld Community</h2>
<p>One of our priority aims regarding ShareWorld Systems is that they be non-alienating, congenial, 
supportive communities for people to enjoy and benefit from.</p>
<p>This is, in the telecommunications world, a tall order.</p>
<p>Most online systems are replete with impediments to community. On the one hand there is intense 
commercialism. Systems are oriented to make a buck, at any cost and users can feel and see this, and the 
prospects for open and understanding exchange suffers.</p>
<p>Also, however, there are problems that arise from users themselves. Systems are fraught with uncivil 
behavior, flaming, harassment of women, etc.</p>
<p>On ShareWorld systems we eliminate these ills and then some. </p>
<p>There is no crass commercialism. Sponsors can sell things like subscriptions or items they promote, and 
there is even an online mall for shopping -- but only socially responsible businesses are welcome, and, 
more to the point, users have to choose to see these offerings. They are not flaunted at every opportunity.</p>
<p>We incorporate various forums devoted to humor, making friends and learning about one another, etc.</p>
<p>We have a system registry for people to enter information in. You double lick on a user id and see the 
personal information they have entered as their online bio...</p>
<p><img src="images/SWcom23.gif" align=bottom width=524 height=363></p>
<p>We have a facility for developing &quot;pen pal&quot; and &quot;buddy&quot; relationships online.</p>
<p><img src="images/SWcom24.gif" align=bottom width=527 height=503></p>
<p>And, all public exchanges are moderated according to our online rules of operations...</p>
<blockquote>
<p>For everyone's safety, no socially illegal actions are permitted, nor will any be tolerated. 
This is a social statement of collective norms of survival for a progressive online system.<br>
<br>
Also, beyond society's limitations, incivility in any form is forbidden on any ShareWorld 
system. This is a moderated system and we intend to ensure that users enjoy a congenial, 
friendly, and respectful environment. In particular, any kind of harassment is forbidden, 
including overt sexism, racism, or classism, of course, but also including any kind of 
demeaning or otherwise hostile disrespect of others. <br>
<br>
Also forbidden is hounding others in any way, even for perfectly respectful ends, such as 
continually emailing or publicly posting messages trying to engage or to continue exchanges 
with folks who have clearly indicated (publicly or privately) their desire to leave an 
exchange.<br>
<br>
Likewise, questioning ideas and claims and offering varied views on matters is of course 
wonderful. But questioning user's private motivations is not.<br>
<br>
Finally, referring in public posts to the views that other people on the system hold without 
incorporating quotes from the people that do in fact make those points, is also frowned upon. <br>
<br>
But, everything not forbidden is welcome. <br>
<br>
</p>
</blockquote>
<h2><img src="images/div.gif" alt="[HRule Image]" align=bottom width=465 height=7> </h2>
<p>To find out more about our systems, their options and functionality, and how our clients and users benefit, 
please choose <a href="serv01.htm">services</a>, here or above. </p>
<p><img src="images/div.gif" alt="[HRule Image]" align=bottom width=465 height=7> </p>
<h2>Contact Information</h2>
<dl>
<dt><strong>Telephone</strong> </dt>
<dd>1-617-862-4500</dd>
<dt><strong>FAX</strong> </dt>
<dd>fax number here</dd>
<dt><strong>Postal address</strong> </dt>
<dd>address here...</dd>
