<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>For Crying Out Loud</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><IMG SRC="header.gif" ALIGN="TOP">
<HR>
<H1><A NAME="Forcryingoutloud">For Crying Out Loud</A></H1>   
<IMG SRC="crying.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
<H2>
Women's Poverty in the United States</H2>
<H3>Edited by Diane Dujon and Ann Withorn</H3>
<P>Welfare reform is once again on the national agenda, and as the debate
unfolds, it is very important to keep the needs of women and children, the
fastest growing population of those in poverty, central to the debate. For
Crying Out Loud challenges the ways that the assault on welfare places blame on
women's shoulders, and ultimately judges all women for the failures of the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>This anthology shows that the situation facing poor women continues to
deteriorate and that their concerns are often denied and misunderstood by
politicians, policy makers, and the media. Although many believe that government
expenditures for the poor are running rampant, in reality only one of every
eight dollares of federal entitlement outlays goes to those living in poverty.
In fact, the rich are subsidized by the government at a greater level than the
poor.</P>
<P>For Crying Out Loud, through the multiplicity of voices addresses  the
complex reasons that women find themselves poor, and the richness of their
efforts to transcend their adversity. This collection trys to move the focus of
the debate away form eliminating welfare to eliminating poverty.
</P>
<P>The writers in this anthology begin to unsnarl the tangled skeins of women's
poverty and weave a richer tapestry, one that presents a vivid picture of
economic, social, and psychological dimensions of economic deprivation. Neither
a laundry list of woes nor a detached academic survey, For Crying Out Loud
combines powerful personal accounts with systematic analysis to present a broad
view, one that includes single mothers, aging widows, black women, Latinas, and
rural women, in a wide-range lens.
</P>
<P>This collection does more than catalog women's strengths and the
difficulties of poverty: its authors review &quot;traditional solutions&quot; to
women's poverty, such as job programs, welfare, and electoral politics, with an
urge to see beyond them to more fundamental change. For Crying Out Loud brings
together a diverse group of authors, including well-known writers and activists
such as Mimi Abramovitz, Frances Fox Piven, and Marian Kramer. 
</P>
<P><I>Diane Dujon is a longtime welfare rights organizer, writer, and former
welfare recipient. Dujon is an administrator at the College of Public and
Community Service at the University of Massachusetts/ Boston. She has worked on
the National Up and Out of Poverty campaigns and is involved with Boston Jobs
for Peace, the Women's Institute for New Growth and Support, and Survival News.</I></P>
<P>$18.00 paper, $40.00 cloth</P>
<HR>
