<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Chaos</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="header.gif" ALIGN="TOP">
<HR>
<H1>Chaos or Community </H1>
<HR>
<H2>Seeking Solutions, Not Scapegoats to Bad Economics</H2>
<H3>By Holly Sklar</H3>
<P>Americans are angry and confused about the state of the economy. The choice
is increasingly a dead-end job or no job, whether the economy is &quot;strong&quot;
or in recession. Wages are way down for younger generations. Once thriving
communities are in decline. Like no other book, <I></I> clears up the confusion
and offers urgent solutions. It has a uniquely sweeping grasp of national and
international economic trends, and how their social and political implications
are felt by the person on the street.</P>
<P>Sklar tells how blame for illegitimate economics is deflected with racist
and sexist scapegoating.  The shrinking American middle class is misled into
thinking those below them on the economic ladder are pulling them down. People
who should be working together to transform harmful economic policies are
instead turning on each other. The &quot;War on Poverty&quot; has given way to
the rollback of welfare. Millions of young people are being written off. Instead
of full employment, the United States has full prisons. The military budget
continues waging the Cold War, while needed programs to prevent violence and
invest in people are being sacrificed. Echoing Martin Luther King's eloquent
appeal to choose community over chaos before it's too late, Sklar offers crucial
steps for changing course, protecting livelihoods, and forging true security and
opportunity.</P>
<P>Holly Sklar's previous works include <I>Streets of Hope: The Fall and Rise
of an Urban Neighborhood</I> (co-authored) and
<I>Trilateralism: The Trilateral Commission and Elite Planning for World
Management</I>, the far-reaching book that foretold the New World Order. She is
a columnist for <I>Z</I> Magazine and has contributed to numerous books and
periodicals, including <I>The Nation,</I> the <I>Philadelphia Inquirer</I> and
<I>USA Today</I>.</P>
<P>$15.00 paper, $35.00 cloth</P>
